<p spacebelow="5" metadata="1:1">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="1:1">1:1</span></font></b> I produced the former account, O Theophilus, about all <u>that</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;of what.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Jesus began to do and to teach, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="1:2">2</span></font></b> until the day he was taken up, <i>[after he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;had given orders&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> had given orders through the Holy Spirit to the apostles whom he had chosen, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="1:3">3</span></font></b> to whom he also presented himself alive after he suffered, with many convincing proofs, appearing to them over a period of forty days and speaking the things about the kingdom of God. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="1:4">4</span></font></b> And <i>[while he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[while]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;was with&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> was with<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;was assembling with,&rdquo; or &ldquo;was sharing a meal with.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> <i>[them]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> he commanded them, &ldquo;Do not depart from Jerusalem, but wait for what was promised by the Father, which you heard about from me. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="1:5">5</span></font></b> For John baptized with water, but you will be baptized with the Holy Spirit <u>not many days from now</u>.&rdquo;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;not many days after these.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="1:6">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="1:6">6</span></font></b> So <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;had come together&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> they had come together, they began asking<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The imperfect tense has been translated as ingressive here (&ldquo;began asking&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> him, saying, &ldquo;Lord, <i>[is it]</i> at this time you are restoring the kingdom to Israel?&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="1:7">7</span></font></b> But he said to them, &ldquo;It is not for you to know <i>[the]</i> times or seasons that the Father has set by his own authority. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="1:8">8</span></font></b> But you will receive power <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;has come&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the Holy Spirit has come upon you, and you will be my witnesses in Jerusalem, and in all Judea and Samaria, and to the farthest part of the earth.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="1:9">9</span></font></b> And <i>[after he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;had said&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> had said these <i>[things]</i>, <i>[while]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[while]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;were watching&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> they were watching, he was taken up, and a cloud received him from their sight. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="1:10">10</span></font></b> And as they were staring into the sky <i>[while]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[while]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;was departing&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> he was departing, behold, two men in white clothing stood by them <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="1:11">11</span></font></b> who also said, &ldquo;Men <u>of Galilee</u>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;Galileans.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> why do you stand there looking<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Some manuscripts have &ldquo;gazing.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> into the sky? This Jesus who was taken up from you into heaven like this will come back in the same way you saw him departing into heaven!&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="1:12">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="1:12">12</span></font></b> Then they returned to Jerusalem from the mountain that is called Olive Grove<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="This is a variation of the name &ldquo;Mount of Olives.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> which is near Jerusalem, <u>a Sabbath day&apos;s journey away</u>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;having a journey of a Sabbath.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="1:13">13</span></font></b> And when they had entered, they went up to the upstairs room where they were staying--Peter and John and James and Andrew, Philip and Thomas, Bartholomew and Matthew, James <i>[son]</i> of Alphaeus and Simon the Zealot and Judas <i>[son]</i> of James. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="1:14">14</span></font></b> All these were busily engaged with one mind in prayer, together with the women and Mary the mother of Jesus and with<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Some manuscripts omit &ldquo;with.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> his brothers. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="1:15">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="1:15">15</span></font></b> And in those days Peter stood up in the midst of the brothers (and it was a crowd of persons of about one hundred twenty at the same <i>[place]</i>) <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;stood up&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="1:16">16</span></font></b> &ldquo;Men <i>[and]</i> brothers, it was necessary <i>[that]</i> the scripture be fulfilled, which the Holy Spirit proclaimed beforehand through the mouth of David concerning Judas, who became a guide to those who arrested Jesus, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="1:17">17</span></font></b> because he was counted among us and received a share in this ministry.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="1:18">18</span></font></b> (Now this man acquired a field for the wages of <i>[his]</i> wickedness, and falling headlong, he burst open in the middle and all his intestines spilled out. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="1:19">19</span></font></b> And it became known to all who live in Jerusalem, so that that field was called in their own language<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="That is, Aramaic."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> &ldquo;Akeldama,&rdquo; that is, &ldquo;Field of Blood.&rdquo;) <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="1:20">20</span></font></b> &ldquo;For it is written in the book of Psalms, &apos;Let his residence become deserted, and let there be no one to live in it,&apos;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A quotation from Ps 69:25."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and, &apos;Let another person take his position.&apos;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A quotation from Ps 109:8."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="1:21">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="1:21">21</span></font></b> Therefore it is necessary for <i>[one]</i> of the men who have accompanied us during all the time <i>[in]</i> which the Lord Jesus went in and went out among us, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="1:22">22</span></font></b> beginning from the baptism of John until the day <i>[on]</i> which he was taken up from us--one of these <i>[men]</i> must become a witness of his resurrection together with us.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="1:23">23</span></font></b> And they proposed two <i>[men]</i>, Joseph called Barsabbas (who was called Justus) and Matthias. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="1:24">24</span></font></b> And they prayed <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;prayed&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said, &ldquo;You, Lord, who know the hearts of all, show clearly which one of these two you have chosen <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="1:25">25</span></font></b> to take the place in this ministry and apostleship from which Judas turned aside to depart to his own place.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="1:26">26</span></font></b> And they cast lots for them, and the lot fell on Matthias, and he was added <i>[to serve]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The words &ldquo;<i>[to serve]</i>&rdquo; are not in the Greek text, but are implied."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> with the eleven apostles. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="2:1">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="2:1">2:1</span></font></b> And when the day of Pentecost had come, they were all together in the same <i>[place]</i>. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="2:2">2</span></font></b> And suddenly a sound like a violent rushing wind came from heaven and filled the whole house where they were sitting. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="2:3">3</span></font></b> And divided<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or perhaps &ldquo;distributed.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> tongues like fire appeared to them and rested on each one of them. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="2:4">4</span></font></b> And they were all filled with the Holy Spirit and began to speak in other languages<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;tongues.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> as the Spirit gave them <i>[ability]</i> to speak out. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="2:5">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="2:5">5</span></font></b> Now there were Jews residing in Jerusalem, devout men from every nation under heaven. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="2:6">6</span></font></b> And <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;happened&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> this sound occurred, the crowd gathered and was in confusion, because each one was hearing them speaking in his own language. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="2:7">7</span></font></b> And they were astounded and astonished, saying, &ldquo;Behold, are not all these who are speaking Galileans? <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="2:8">8</span></font></b> And how do we hear, each one <i>[of us]</i>, in <u>our own native language</u>?<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;our own language in which we were born.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="2:9">9</span></font></b> Parthians and Medes and Elamites and those residing <i>[in]</i> Mesopotamia, Judea and Cappadocia, Pontus and Asia,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A reference to the Roman province of Asia (modern Asia Minor)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="2:10">10</span></font></b> Phrygia and Pamphylia, Egypt and the parts of Libya toward Cyrene, and the Romans who were in town, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="2:11">11</span></font></b> both Jews and proselytes, Cretans and Arabs--we hear them speaking in our <i>[own]</i> languages the great deeds of God!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="2:12">12</span></font></b> And all were amazed and greatly perplexed, saying <u>to one another</u>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;one to the other.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> &ldquo;<u>What can this mean?</u>&rdquo;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;what does this want to be.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="2:13">13</span></font></b> But others jeered <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;jeered&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said, &ldquo;They are full of sweet new wine!&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="2:14">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="2:14">14</span></font></b> But Peter, standing with the eleven, raised his voice and declared to them, &ldquo;Judean men, and all those who live <i>[in]</i> Jerusalem, let this be known to you, and pay attention to my words! <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="2:15">15</span></font></b> For these <i>[men]</i> are not drunk, as you assume, because it is the third hour of the day. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="2:16">16</span></font></b> But this is what was spoken through the prophet Joel: </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="2:17">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="2:17">17</span></font></b> &apos;And it will be in the last days,&apos; God says, &apos;I will pour out my Spirit on all flesh, and your sons and your daughters will prophesy, and your young men will see visions, and your old men will dream dreams. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="2:18">18</span></font></b> And even on my male slaves and on my female slaves I will pour out my Spirit in those days, and they will prophesy. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="2:19">19</span></font></b> And I will cause wonders in the heaven<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;sky.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> above and signs on the earth below, blood and fire and vapor of smoke. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="2:20">20</span></font></b> The sun will be changed to darkness and the moon to blood, before the great and glorious day of the Lord comes. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="2:21">21</span></font></b> And it will be <i>[that]</i> everyone who calls upon the name of the Lord will be saved.&apos;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A quotation from Joel 2:28-32."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="2:22">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="2:22">22</span></font></b> &ldquo;Israelite men, listen to these words! Jesus the Nazarene, a man attested to you by God with deeds of power and wonders and signs that God did through him in your midst, just as <i>[you]</i> yourselves know-- <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="2:23">23</span></font></b> this man, delivered up by the determined plan and foreknowledge of God, you executed <i>[by]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[by]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;nailing to&rdquo;) which is understood as means."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> nailing to <i>[a cross]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The words &ldquo;<i>[a cross]</i>&rdquo; are not in the Greek text but are implied by the nature of the verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> through the hand of lawless men. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="2:24">24</span></font></b> God raised <u>him</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;whom&rdquo;; it is necessary to specify &ldquo;him&rdquo; in the translation to avoid confusion with the &ldquo;lawless men&rdquo; in the previous verse."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> up, having brought to an end the pains of death, because it was not possible <i>[for]</i> him to be held by it. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="2:25">25</span></font></b> For David says with reference to him, &apos;I saw the Lord before me <u>continually</u>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;through everything.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> for he is at my right hand so that I will not be shaken. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="2:26">26</span></font></b> For this <i>[reason]</i> my heart was glad and my tongue rejoiced greatly, furthermore also my flesh will live in hope, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="2:27">27</span></font></b> because you will not abandon my soul in Hades, nor will you permit your Holy One to experience decay. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="2:28">28</span></font></b> You have made known to me the paths of life; you will fill me with gladness with your presence.&apos;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A quotation from Ps 16:8-11."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="2:29">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="2:29">29</span></font></b> &ldquo;Men <i>[and]</i> brothers, it is possible to speak with confidence to you about the patriarch David, that he both died and was buried, and his tomb is with us until this day. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="2:30">30</span></font></b> Therefore, <i>[because he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[because]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;was&rdquo;) which is understood as causal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> was a prophet and knew that God had sworn to him with an oath to seat <u>one of his descendants</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;from the fruit of his loins.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> on his throne, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="2:31">31</span></font></b> <i>[by]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[by]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;having foreseen&rdquo;) which is understood as means."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> having foreseen <i>[this]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> he spoke about the resurrection of the Christ,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;Messiah.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> that neither was he abandoned in Hades nor did his flesh experience decay. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="2:32">32</span></font></b> This Jesus God raised up, of which<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;of whom,&rdquo; referring to Jesus."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> we all are witnesses. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="2:33">33</span></font></b> Therefore, having been exalted to the right hand of God and having received the promise of the Holy Spirit from the Father, he has poured out this that you see and hear.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Some manuscripts have &ldquo;both see and hear.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="2:34">34</span></font></b> For David did not ascend into heaven, but he himself says, &apos;The Lord said to my Lord, &ldquo;Sit at my right hand, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="2:35">35</span></font></b> until I make your enemies a footstool for your feet.&rdquo; &apos;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A quotation from Ps 110:1."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="2:36">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="2:36">36</span></font></b> Therefore let all the house of Israel know beyond a doubt, that God has made him both Lord and Christ--this Jesus whom you crucified!&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="2:37">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="2:37">37</span></font></b> Now <i>[when they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;heard&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> heard <i>[this]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> they were pierced to the heart and said to Peter and the other apostles, &ldquo;What should we do, men <i>[and]</i> brothers?&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="2:38">38</span></font></b> And Peter <i>[said]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Some manuscripts explicitly add &ldquo;said.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to them, &ldquo;Repent and be baptized, each one of you, in the name of Jesus Christ for the forgiveness of your sins, and you will receive the gift of the Holy Spirit. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="2:39">39</span></font></b> For the promise is for you and for your children, and for all those <i>[who are]</i> far away, as many as the Lord our God calls to himself.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="2:40">40</span></font></b> And with many other words he solemnly urged and exhorted them, saying, &ldquo;Be saved from this crooked generation!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="2:41">41</span></font></b> So those who accepted his message were baptized, and on that day about three thousand souls were added. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="2:42">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="2:42">42</span></font></b> And they were devoting themselves to the teaching of the apostles and to fellowship, to the breaking of bread and to prayers. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="2:43">43</span></font></b> And fear came on every soul, and many wonders and signs were being performed by the apostles. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="2:44">44</span></font></b> And all who believed were in the same <i>[place]</i>, and had everything in common. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="2:45">45</span></font></b> And they began selling<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The imperfect tense has been translated as ingressive here (&ldquo;began selling&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> <i>[their]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> possessions and property, and distributing these <i>[things]</i> to all, to the degree that anyone had need. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="2:46">46</span></font></b> And every day, devoting themselves <i>[to meeting]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The words &ldquo;<i>[to meeting]</i>&rdquo; are not in the Greek text but are implied."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> with one purpose in the temple <i>[courts]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[courts]</i>&rdquo; is supplied to distinguish this area from the interior of the temple building itself."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and breaking bread from house <i>[to house]</i>, they were eating <i>[their]</i> food with joy and simplicity of heart, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="2:47">47</span></font></b> praising God and having favor with all the people. And the Lord was adding every day to the total <i>[of]</i> those who were being saved. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="3:1">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="3:1">3:1</span></font></b> Now Peter and John were going up to the temple at the hour of prayer, the ninth <i>[hour]</i>. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="3:2">2</span></font></b> And a certain man was being carried who was lame <u>from birth</u>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;from his mother&apos;s womb.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> <u>He</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;who,&rdquo; but a new sentence was begun here in the translation in keeping with English style."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> was placed every day at the gate of the temple called &ldquo;Beautiful,&rdquo; <i>[so that he]</i> could ask for charitable gifts from those who were going into the temple <i>[courts]</i>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[courts]</i>&rdquo; is supplied to distinguish this area from the interior of the temple building itself."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="3:3">3</span></font></b> <i>[When he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;saw&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> saw Peter and John about to go into the temple <i>[courts]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[courts]</i>&rdquo; is supplied to distinguish this area from the interior of the temple building itself."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> he began asking to receive alms. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="3:4">4</span></font></b> And Peter looked intently at him, together with John, <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;looked intently&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said, &ldquo;Look at us!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="3:5">5</span></font></b> So he fixed his attention on them, expecting to receive something from them. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="3:6">6</span></font></b> But Peter said, &ldquo;Silver and gold <u>I do not possess</u>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;is not to me.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> but what I have, this I give to you--in the name of Jesus Christ the Nazarene, walk!&rdquo;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Some manuscripts have &ldquo;get up and walk.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="3:7">7</span></font></b> And taking hold of him by the right hand, he raised him up, and immediately his feet and ankles were made strong. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="3:8">8</span></font></b> And leaping up, he stood and began walking around<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The imperfect tense has been translated as ingressive here (&ldquo;began walking around&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and entered into the temple <i>[courts]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[courts]</i>&rdquo; is supplied to distinguish this area from the interior of the temple building itself."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> with them, walking and leaping and praising God. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="3:9">9</span></font></b> And all the people saw him walking and praising God, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="3:10">10</span></font></b> And they recognized him, that this one<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Some manuscripts have &ldquo;that <i>[he]</i> himself.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> was the one who used to sit <i>[asking]</i> for alms at the Beautiful Gate of the temple, and they were filled with awe and astonishment at what had happened to him. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="3:11">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="3:11">11</span></font></b> And <i>[while]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[while]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;was holding fast to&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> he was holding fast to Peter and John, all the people ran together to them in the portico called Solomon&apos;s, utterly astonished. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="3:12">12</span></font></b> And <i>[when he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;saw&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> saw <i>[it]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Peter replied to the people, &ldquo;Men <i>[and]</i> Israelites, why are you astonished at this? Or why are you staring at us, as <i>[if]</i> by our own power or godliness we have made him walk? <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="3:13">13</span></font></b> The God of Abraham and of Isaac<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Some manuscripts have &ldquo;the God of Isaac.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and of Jacob,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Some manuscripts have &ldquo;the God of Jacob.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the God of our fathers, has glorified his servant Jesus, whom you handed over and denied in the presence of Pilate, <i>[after]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;<i>[although]</i>&rdquo;; this genitive absolute construction can be understood as either temporal &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; or concessive &ldquo;<i>[although]</i>.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> he had decided to release <i>[him]</i>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="3:14">14</span></font></b> But you denied the Holy and Righteous One and demanded <i>[that]</i> a man--a murderer--be granted to you. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="3:15">15</span></font></b> And you killed the originator of life, whom God raised from the dead, of which we are witnesses! <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="3:16">16</span></font></b> And on the basis of faith in his name, his name has made this man strong, whom you see and know, and the faith <i>[that is]</i> through him has given him this perfect health in the presence of you all. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="3:17">17</span></font></b> And now, brothers, I know that you acted in ignorance, just as your rulers did also. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="3:18">18</span></font></b> But <i>[the things]</i> which God foretold through the mouth of all the prophets, <i>[that]</i> his Christ<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;Messiah.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> would suffer, he has fulfilled in this way. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="3:19">19</span></font></b> Therefore repent and turn back, so that your sins may be blotted out, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="3:20">20</span></font></b> so that times of refreshing may come from the presence of the Lord, and he may send the Christ<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;Messiah.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> appointed for you--Jesus, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="3:21">21</span></font></b> whom heaven must receive until the times of the restoration of all <i>[things]</i>, about which God spoke through the mouth of his holy prophets from earliest times. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="3:22">22</span></font></b> Moses said, &apos;The Lord God<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Some manuscripts have &ldquo;The Lord your God.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> will raise up for you a prophet like me from your brothers. You will listen to him in everything that he says to you.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A quotation from Deut 18:15."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="3:23">23</span></font></b> And it will be <i>[that]</i> every soul who does not listen to that prophet will be destroyed utterly from the people.&apos;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A quotation from Deut 18:19 and Lev 23:29."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="3:24">24</span></font></b> And indeed, all the prophets from Samuel and all those who followed <i>[him]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> have spoken <i>[about]</i> and proclaimed these days. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="3:25">25</span></font></b> You are the sons of the prophets and of the covenant that God ordained with your fathers, saying to Abraham, &apos;And in your offspring all the nations of the earth will be blessed.&apos;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A quotation from Gen 22:18."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="3:26">26</span></font></b> God, <i>[after he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;had raised up&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> had raised up his servant, sent him to you first, to bless you by turning each <i>[of you]</i> back from your wickedness!&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="4:1">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="4:1">4:1</span></font></b> And <i>[while]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[while]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;were speaking&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> they were speaking to the people, the priests and the captain of the temple and the Sadducees approached them, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="4:2">2</span></font></b> greatly annoyed because they were teaching the people and proclaiming in Jesus the resurrection from the dead. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="4:3">3</span></font></b> And they laid hands on them and put <i>[them]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> in custody until the next day, because it was already evening. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="4:4">4</span></font></b> But many of those who listened to the message believed, and the number of the men was approximately five thousand. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="4:5">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="4:5">5</span></font></b> And it happened that on the next day, their rulers and elders and scribes came together in Jerusalem, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="4:6">6</span></font></b> and Annas the high priest, and Caiaphas and John and Alexander, and all those who were from the high priest&apos;s family. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="4:7">7</span></font></b> And they made them stand in <i>[their]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> midst <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;stand&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> began to ask,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The imperfect tense has been translated as ingressive here (&ldquo;began to ask&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> &ldquo;By what power or by what name did you do this?&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="4:8">8</span></font></b> Then Peter, filled with the Holy Spirit, said to them, &ldquo;Rulers of the people and elders, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="4:9">9</span></font></b> if we are being examined today concerning a good deed <i>[done to]</i> a sick man--by what <i>[means]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;through whom.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> this man was healed-- <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="4:10">10</span></font></b> let it be known to all of you and to all the people of Israel that by the name of Jesus Christ the Nazarene, whom you crucified, whom God raised from the dead--by him this man stands before you healthy! <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="4:11">11</span></font></b> This one<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="&ldquo;This one&rdquo; refers to Jesus."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> is the stone that was rejected by you, the builders, that has become <u>the cornerstone</u>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the head of the corner&rdquo;; this verse is an allusion to Ps 118:22."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="4:12">12</span></font></b> And there is salvation in no one else, for there is no other name under heaven that is given among people by which we must be saved.&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="4:13">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="4:13">13</span></font></b> Now <i>[when they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;saw&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> saw the boldness of Peter and John, and understood that they were uneducated and untrained men, they were astonished, and recognized them, that they had been with Jesus. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="4:14">14</span></font></b> And <i>[because they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[because]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;saw&rdquo;) which is understood as causal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> saw the man who had been healed standing there with them, they had nothing to say in return. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="4:15">15</span></font></b> But <i>[after they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;had ordered&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> had ordered them to go outside the Sanhedrin,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;council.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> they began to confer<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The imperfect tense has been translated as ingressive here (&ldquo;began to confer&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> with one another, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="4:16">16</span></font></b> saying, &ldquo;What should we do with these men? For that a remarkable sign has taken place through them <i>[is]</i> evident to all those who live <i>[in]</i> Jerusalem, and we are not able to deny <i>[it]</i>!<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="4:17">17</span></font></b> But in order that it may not spread much <i>[further]</i> among the people, let us warn them to speak no more in this name <u>to anyone at all</u>.&rdquo;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;to no man.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="4:18">18</span></font></b> And they called them <i>[back]</i> <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;called&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> commanded <i>[them]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> not to speak or to teach at all in the name of Jesus. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="4:19">19</span></font></b> But Peter and John answered <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;answered&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said to them, &ldquo;Whether it is right in the sight of God to listen to you rather than God, you decide! <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="4:20">20</span></font></b> For we are not able to refrain from speaking about <i>[the things]</i> that we have seen and heard.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="4:21">21</span></font></b> So <i>[after]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;threatening ... further&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> threatening <i>[them]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> further, they released them, finding no way to punish them on account of the people, because they were all praising God for what had happened. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="4:22">22</span></font></b> For the man on whom this sign of healing had been performed was more <i>[than]</i> forty years <i>[old]</i>. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="4:23">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="4:23">23</span></font></b> And <i>[when they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;were released&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> were released, they went to their own <i>[people]</i> and reported all that the chief priests and the elders had said to them. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="4:24">24</span></font></b> And <i>[when they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;heard&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> heard <i>[it]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> they lifted <i>[their]</i> voices with one mind to God and said, &ldquo;Master, you <i>[are]</i> the one who made the heaven and the earth and the sea and all the things in them, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="4:25">25</span></font></b> the one who said by the Holy Spirit through the mouth of our father David, your servant, &apos;Why do the nations<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;Gentiles&rdquo;; the same Greek word can be translated &ldquo;nations&rdquo; or &ldquo;Gentiles&rdquo; depending on the context."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> rage, and the peoples conspire in vain? <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="4:26">26</span></font></b> The kings of the earth stood opposed, and the rulers assembled together at the same <i>[place]</i>, against the Lord and against his Christ.&apos;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;Messiah&rdquo;; this is a quotation from Ps 2:1-2."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="4:27">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="4:27">27</span></font></b> For in truth both Herod and Pontius Pilate, together with the Gentiles and the peoples of Israel, assembled together in this city against your holy servant Jesus whom you anointed, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="4:28">28</span></font></b> to do all that your hand and plan<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Some manuscripts have &ldquo;and your plan.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> had predestined to take place. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="4:29">29</span></font></b> And now, Lord, concern yourself with their threats and grant your slaves to speak your message with all boldness, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="4:30">30</span></font></b> <i>[as]</i> you extend your hand to heal and signs and wonders are performed through the name of your holy servant Jesus.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="4:31">31</span></font></b> And <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;had prayed&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> they had prayed, the place in which they were gathered was shaken, and they were all filled with the Holy Spirit and began to speak<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The imperfect tense has been translated as ingressive here (&ldquo;began to speak&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the word<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;message.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> of God with boldness. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="4:32">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="4:32">32</span></font></b> Now the group of those who believed were one heart and soul, and no one said anything of what belonged to him was his own, but all <i>[things]</i> were theirs in common. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="4:33">33</span></font></b> And with great power the apostles were giving testimony <i>[to]</i> the resurrection of the Lord Jesus, and great grace was on them all. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="4:34">34</span></font></b> For there was not even anyone needy among them, because all those who were owners of plots of land or houses were selling <i>[them]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;were selling&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> bringing the proceeds of the things that were sold <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="4:35">35</span></font></b> and placing <i>[them]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> at the feet of the apostles. And it was being distributed to each as anyone had need. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="4:36">36</span></font></b> So Joseph, who was called Barnabas by the apostles (which is translated &ldquo;son of encouragement&rdquo;), a Levite of Cyprus by nationality, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="4:37">37</span></font></b> sold a field<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;a farm.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> that belonged to him <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;sold&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> brought the money and placed <i>[it]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> at the feet of the apostles. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="5:1">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:1">5:1</span></font></b> Now a certain man <u>named</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;by name.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Ananias, together with his wife Sapphira, sold a piece of property, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:2">2</span></font></b> and he kept back for himself <i>[some]</i> of the proceeds, and <i>[his]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> wife was aware of <i>[it]</i>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the participle &ldquo;was aware of&rdquo; in this genitive absolute construction has been translated as a finite verb in keeping with English style."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> And he brought a certain part <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;brought&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> placed <i>[it]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> at the feet of the apostles. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:3">3</span></font></b> But Peter said, &ldquo;Ananias, for what <i>[reason]</i> has Satan filled your heart, <i>[that]</i> you lied to the Holy Spirit and kept back for yourself <i>[some]</i> of the proceeds of the piece of land? <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:4">4</span></font></b> <i>[When it]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;remained&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> remained to you, did it not remain <i>[yours]</i>? And <i>[when it]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;was sold&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> was sold, was it at your disposal? How <i>[is it]</i> that you have contrived this deed in your heart? You have not lied to people, but to God!&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="5:5">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:5">5</span></font></b> And <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;heard&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Ananias heard these words, he fell down <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;fell down&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> died. And great fear came on all those who heard about <i>[it]</i>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:6">6</span></font></b> So the young men stood up, wrapped him up, and carried <i>[him]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> out <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;carried ... out&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> buried <i>[him]</i>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:7">7</span></font></b> And it happened that <i>[there was]</i> an interval of about three hours, and his wife came in, not knowing what had happened. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:8">8</span></font></b> And Peter said to her, &ldquo;Tell me whether you <i>[both]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[both]</i>&rdquo; reflects the second person plural verb, which refers to both Ananias and Sapphira."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> were paid this much <i>[for]</i> the piece of land.&rdquo; And she said, &ldquo;Yes, this much.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:9">9</span></font></b> So Peter <i>[said]</i> to her, &ldquo;How <i>[is it]</i> that it was agreed by you <i>[two]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[two]</i>&rdquo; is supplied in the translation to indicate that the pronoun (&ldquo;you&rdquo;) is plural in the Greek text."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to test the Spirit of the Lord? Behold, the feet of those who buried your husband <i>[are]</i> at the door, and they will carry you out!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:10">10</span></font></b> And immediately she fell down at his feet and died. So <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;came in&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the young men came in, they found her dead, and carried <i>[her]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> out <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;carried ... out&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> buried <i>[her]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> with her husband. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:11">11</span></font></b> And great fear came on the whole church and on all who heard about these <i>[things]</i>. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="5:12">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:12">12</span></font></b> Now many signs and wonders were being performed among the people through the hands of the apostles. And they were all together<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or perhaps &ldquo;by common consent.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> in Solomon&apos;s Portico. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:13">13</span></font></b> And none of the rest dared to join them, but the people spoke highly of them. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:14">14</span></font></b> And even more believers in the Lord<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;even more believers were being added to the Lord.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> were being added, large numbers of both men and women, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:15">15</span></font></b> so that they even carried out the sick into the streets and put <i>[them]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> on cots and mats<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;mattresses.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> so that <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;came by&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Peter came by, at least <i>[his]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> shadow would fall on some of them. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:16">16</span></font></b> And the people of the towns around Jerusalem also came together, bringing the sick and those tormented by unclean spirits, who were all being healed. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="5:17">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:17">17</span></font></b> Now the high priest rose up and all those <i>[who were]</i> with him (that is, the party of the Sadducees), <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;rose up&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> they were filled with jealousy. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:18">18</span></font></b> And they laid hands on the apostles and put them in the public prison. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:19">19</span></font></b> But during the night an angel of the Lord opened the doors of the prison and led them <i>[out]</i> <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the two previous participles (&ldquo;opened&rdquo; and &ldquo;led&rdquo;) have been translated as finite verbs."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:20">20</span></font></b> &ldquo;Go and stand in the temple <i>[courts]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[courts]</i>&rdquo; is supplied to distinguish this area from the interior of the temple building itself."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;stand&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> proclaim to the people all the words of this life.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:21">21</span></font></b> And <i>[when they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;heard&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> heard <i>[this]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> they entered at daybreak into the temple <i>[courts]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[courts]</i>&rdquo; is supplied to distinguish this area from the interior of the temple building itself."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and began teaching.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The imperfect tense has been translated as ingressive here (&ldquo;began teaching&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Now <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;arrived&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the high priest and those with him arrived, they summoned the Sanhedrin--even the whole council of elders of the sons of Israel--and sent to the prison to have them brought. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:22">22</span></font></b> But the officers who came<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;<i>[when they]</i> came.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> did not find them in the prison, and they returned <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;returned&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> reported, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:23">23</span></font></b> saying, &ldquo;We found the prison locked with all security and the guards standing at the doors, but <i>[when we]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;opened&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> opened <i>[them]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> we found no one inside!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:24">24</span></font></b> Now when both the captain of the temple and the chief priests heard these words, they were greatly perplexed concerning them, <i>[as to]</i> what this might be. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:25">25</span></font></b> But someone came <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;came&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> reported to them, &ldquo;Behold, the men whom you put in prison are standing in the temple <i>[courts]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[courts]</i>&rdquo; is supplied to distinguish this area from the interior of the temple building itself."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and teaching the people!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:26">26</span></font></b> Then the captain went with the officers <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;went&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> brought them, not with force (for they were afraid of the people, lest they be stoned <i>[by them]</i>).<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The words &ldquo;<i>[by them]</i>&rdquo; are not in the Greek text but are implied."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="5:27">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:27">27</span></font></b> And <i>[when they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;had brought&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> had brought them, they made <i>[them]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> stand in the Sanhedrin,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;council.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and the high priest put a question to them, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:28">28</span></font></b> saying, &ldquo;<u>We strictly commanded</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;we commanded with a commandment.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> you<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Some manuscripts have &ldquo;Did we not strictly command you.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> not to teach in this name? And behold, you have filled Jerusalem with your teaching! And you are intending to bring upon us the blood of this man!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:29">29</span></font></b> But Peter and the apostles answered <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;answered&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said, &ldquo;It is necessary to obey God rather than men! <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:30">30</span></font></b> The God of our fathers raised up Jesus, whom you killed <i>[by]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[by]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;hanging&rdquo;) which is understood as means."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> hanging <i>[him]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> on a tree. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:31">31</span></font></b> This one God has exalted to his right hand <i>[as]</i> Leader and Savior to grant repentance to Israel and forgiveness of sins. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:32">32</span></font></b> And we are witnesses of these things, and <i>[so is]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The words &ldquo;<i>[so is]</i>&rdquo; are not in the Greek text but are implied."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the Holy Spirit whom God has given to those who obey him.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:33">33</span></font></b> Now <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;heard&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> they heard <i>[this]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> they were infuriated, and were wanting to execute them. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:34">34</span></font></b> But a certain man stood up in the Sanhedrin,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;council.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> a Pharisee <u>named</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;by name.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Gamaliel, a teacher of the law respected by all the people, <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;stood up&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> gave orders to put the men outside for a short time. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:35">35</span></font></b> And he said to them, &ldquo;Men <i>[and]</i> Israelites, take care for yourselves what you are about to do to these men! <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:36">36</span></font></b> For before these days, Theudas rose up saying he was somebody. A number of men, about four hundred, joined <u>him</u>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;to whom.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> <u>He</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;who.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> was executed, and all who followed him were dispersed and came to nothing. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:37">37</span></font></b> After this man, Judas the Galilean rose up in the days of the census and <u>caused people to follow him in revolt</u>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;caused people to revolt after him.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> And that one perished, and all who followed him were scattered. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:38">38</span></font></b> And now I tell you, keep away from these men, and leave them alone, because if this plan or this matter is from people, it will be overthrown.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;it will fail.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:39">39</span></font></b> But if it is from God, you will not be able to overthrow them, lest you even be found fighting against God.&rdquo; So they were persuaded by him. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:40">40</span></font></b> And they summoned the apostles, beat <i>[them]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> commanded <i>[them]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> not to speak in the name of Jesus, and released <i>[them]</i>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:41">41</span></font></b> So they went out from the presence of the Sanhedrin<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;council.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> rejoicing, because they had been considered worthy to be dishonored for the sake of the name. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:42">42</span></font></b> Every day, both in the temple <i>[courts]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[courts]</i>&rdquo; is supplied to distinguish this area from the interior of the temple building itself."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and from house <i>[to house]</i>, they did not stop teaching and proclaiming the good news <i>[that]</i> the Christ<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;Messiah.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> <i>[was]</i> Jesus. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="6:1">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="6:1">6:1</span></font></b> Now in these days, <i>[as]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[as]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;were increasing&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the disciples were increasing <i>[in number]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The words &ldquo;<i>[in number]</i>&rdquo; are not in the Greek text but are implied."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> a complaint arose by the <u>Greek-speaking Jews</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;Hellenists.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> against the <u>Hebraic Jews</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;Hebrews.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> because<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;that.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> their widows were being overlooked in the daily distribution <i>[of food]</i>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The words &ldquo;<i>[of food]</i>&rdquo; are not in the Greek text but are implied."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="6:2">2</span></font></b> So the twelve summoned the community of disciples <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;summoned&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said, &ldquo;It is not desirable <i>[that]</i> we neglect the word of God to serve tables. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="6:3">3</span></font></b> So, brothers, select from among you seven men <u>of good reputation</u>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;well spoken of.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> full of the Spirit and wisdom, whom we will put in charge of this need. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="6:4">4</span></font></b> But we will devote ourselves to prayer and to the ministry of the word.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="6:5">5</span></font></b> And the statement pleased the whole group, and they chose Stephen (a man full of faith and of the Holy Spirit), and Philip, and Prochorus, and Nicanor, and Timon, and Parmenas, and Nicolaus (a convert from Antioch), <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="6:6">6</span></font></b> whom they stood before the apostles. And they prayed <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;prayed&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> placed <i>[their]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> hands on them. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="6:7">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="6:7">7</span></font></b> And the word of God kept spreading, and the number of disciples in Jerusalem was increasing greatly, and a large number of priests began obeying<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The imperfect tense has been translated as ingressive here (&ldquo;began obeying&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the faith. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="6:8">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="6:8">8</span></font></b> Now Stephen, full of grace and power, was performing great wonders and signs among the people. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="6:9">9</span></font></b> But some of those from the Synagogue of the Freedmen (<u>as it was called</u>),<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;called.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> both Cyrenians and Alexandrians, and those from Cilicia and Asia,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A reference to the Roman province of Asia (modern Asia Minor)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> stood up <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the participle (&ldquo;disputed&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb in keeping with English style."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> disputed with Stephen. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="6:10">10</span></font></b> And they were not able to resist the wisdom and the Spirit with which he was speaking. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="6:11">11</span></font></b> Then they secretly instigated men who said, &ldquo;We have heard him speaking blasphemous words against Moses and God!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="6:12">12</span></font></b> And they incited the people and the elders and the scribes, and they came up <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;came up&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> seized him and brought <i>[him]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to the Sanhedrin.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;council.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="6:13">13</span></font></b> And they put forward false witnesses who said, &ldquo;This man does not stop speaking words against the holy place<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Some manuscripts have &ldquo;this holy place.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and the law! <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="6:14">14</span></font></b> For we have heard him saying that this Nazarene Jesus will destroy this place and will change the customs that Moses handed down to us.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="6:15">15</span></font></b> And <i>[as they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[as]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;looked intently&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> looked intently at him, all those who were sitting in the Sanhedrin<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;council.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> saw his face <i>[was]</i> like the face of an angel. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="7:1">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:1">7:1</span></font></b> And the high priest said, &ldquo;Is it so concerning these <i>[things]</i>?&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:2">2</span></font></b> So he said, &ldquo;Men--brothers and fathers--listen: The God of glory appeared to our father Abraham <i>[while he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[while]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;was&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> was in Mesopotamia, before he settled in Haran, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:3">3</span></font></b> and said to him, &apos;Go out from your land and from your relatives and come to the land that I will show you.&apos; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:4">4</span></font></b> Then he went out from the land of the Chaldeans <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;went out&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> settled in Haran. And from there, after his father died, he caused him to move to this land in which you now live. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:5">5</span></font></b> And he did not give him an inheritance in it--not even a footstep<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;a step of a foot.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> --and he promised to give <i>[it]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to him for his possession, and to his descendants after him, <u>although he did not have</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;not being to him.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> <font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[although]</i>&rdquo; is supplied in the translation as a component of the participle (&ldquo;was&rdquo;) which is understood as concessive."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> a child. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:6">6</span></font></b> But God spoke like this: &apos;His descendants will be foreigners in a foreign land, and they will enslave them and mistreat <i>[them]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> four hundred years, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:7">7</span></font></b> and the nation <u>that</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;to which.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> they will serve as slaves, I will judge,&apos; God said, &apos;and after these <i>[things]</i> they will come out<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Verses 6-7 are a quotation from Gen 15:13-14."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and will worship me in this place.&apos;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The final phrase is an allusion to Exod 3:12."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:8">8</span></font></b> And he gave him the covenant of circumcision, and so he became the father of Isaac and circumcised him on the eighth day, and Isaac <i>[did so with]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the words &ldquo;<i>[did so with]</i>&rdquo; are not in the Greek text but are implied; in view of the &ldquo;covenant of circumcision&rdquo; mentioned earlier in the verse, it is probable that circumcision and not just fatherhood is involved."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Jacob, and Jacob <i>[did so with]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the words &ldquo;<i>[did so with]</i>&rdquo; are not in the Greek text but are implied; see the note on the same phrase earlier in this verse."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the twelve patriarchs. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:9">9</span></font></b> And the patriarchs, <i>[because they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[because]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;were jealous of&rdquo;) which is understood as causal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> were jealous of Joseph, sold <i>[him]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> into Egypt. And God was with him, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:10">10</span></font></b> and rescued him from all his afflictions and granted him favor and wisdom in the sight of Pharaoh king of Egypt. And he appointed him ruler over Egypt and all<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Some manuscripts have &ldquo;over all.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> his household. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:11">11</span></font></b> And a famine came over all Egypt and Canaan and great affliction, and our fathers could not find food. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:12">12</span></font></b> So <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;heard&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Jacob heard <i>[there]</i> was grain in Egypt, he sent out our fathers first. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:13">13</span></font></b> And on the second <i>[visit]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The word &ldquo;<i>[visit]</i>&rdquo; is not in the Greek text but is implied."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Joseph was made known to his brothers, and the family of Joseph became known to Pharaoh. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:14">14</span></font></b> So Joseph sent <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;sent&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> summoned his father Jacob and all <i>[his]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> relatives, seventy-five persons in <i>[all]</i>. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:15">15</span></font></b> And Jacob went down to Egypt and died, he and our fathers. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:16">16</span></font></b> And they were brought back to Shechem and buried in the tomb that Abraham had bought for a sum of silver from the sons of Hamor in Shechem. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="7:17">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:17">17</span></font></b> &ldquo;But as the time of the promise that God had made to Abraham was drawing near, the people increased and multiplied in Egypt <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:18">18</span></font></b> until another king arose over Egypt who did not know Joseph. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:19">19</span></font></b> This man deceitfully took advantage of our<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> people <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;deceitfully took advantage of&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> mistreated our ancestors, <u>causing them to abandon their infants</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;making their infants be abandoned.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> so that they would not be kept alive. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:20">20</span></font></b> At this time Moses was born, and he was beautiful to God. <u>He</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;who.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> was brought up <i>[for]</i> three months in <i>[his]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> father&apos;s house, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:21">21</span></font></b> and <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;was abandoned&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> he was abandoned, the daughter of Pharaoh took him <i>[up]</i> and brought him <i>[up]</i> <u>as her own son</u>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;for a son to herself.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:22">22</span></font></b> And Moses was educated in all the wisdom of the Egyptians, and was powerful in his words and deeds. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="7:23">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:23">23</span></font></b> &ldquo;But when <u>he was forty years old</u>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;a period of time of forty years was fulfilled for him.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> it entered in his heart to visit his brothers, the sons of Israel. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:24">24</span></font></b> And <i>[when he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;saw&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> saw one of them being unjustly harmed, he defended <i>[him]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and <u>avenged</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;produced vengeance <i>[for]</i>.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the one who had been oppressed <i>[by]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[by]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;striking down&rdquo;) which is understood as means."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> striking down the Egyptian. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:25">25</span></font></b> And he thought his<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> brothers would understand that God was granting deliverance to them by his hand, but they did not understand. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:26">26</span></font></b> And on the following day, he made an appearance to them <i>[while they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[while]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;were fighting&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> were fighting and was attempting to reconcile<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the imperfect verb has been translated as conative (&ldquo;was attempting to reconcile&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> them in peace, saying, &apos;Men <i>[and]</i> brothers, why are you doing wrong to one another?&apos; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:27">27</span></font></b> But the one who was doing wrong to <i>[his]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> neighbor pushed him aside, saying, &apos;Who appointed you a ruler and a judge over us? <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:28">28</span></font></b> You do not want to do away with me <u>the same way</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;in the manner in which.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> you did away with the Egyptian yesterday, <i>[do you]</i>?&apos;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A quotation from Exod 2:14; the negative construction in Greek anticipates a negative answer here, indicated by &ldquo;<i>[do you]</i>.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:29">29</span></font></b> And at this statement, Moses fled and became a foreigner in the land of Midian, where he became the father of two sons. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="7:30">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:30">30</span></font></b> &ldquo;And <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;had been completed&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> forty years had been completed, an angel appeared to him in the desert of Mount Sinai in the flame of a burning bush. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:31">31</span></font></b> And <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;saw&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Moses saw <i>[it]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> he was astonished at the sight, and <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;approached&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> he approached to look at <i>[it]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the voice of the Lord came: <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:32">32</span></font></b> &apos;I <i>[am]</i> the God of your fathers, the God of Abraham and of Isaac and of Jacob!&apos;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A quotation from Exod 3:6."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> So Moses began trembling <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;began&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> did not dare to look at <i>[it]</i>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:33">33</span></font></b> And the Lord said to him, &apos;Untie the sandals from your feet, for the place on which you are standing is holy ground. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:34">34</span></font></b> <u>I have certainly seen</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;seeing I have seen.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the mistreatment of my people <i>[who are]</i> in Egypt and have heard their groaning, and I have come down to deliver them. And now come, I will send you to Egypt.&apos;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A quotation from Exod 3:5, 7-8, 10."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:35">35</span></font></b> This Moses whom they had repudiated, saying, &apos;Who appointed you a ruler and a judge?&apos;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A quotation from Exod 2:14 (see v. 27 above)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> --this man God sent <i>[as]</i> both ruler and redeemer with <u>the help</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;hand.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> of the angel who appeared to him in the bush. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:36">36</span></font></b> This man led them out, performing wonders and signs in the land of Egypt and at the Red Sea and in the wilderness <i>[for]</i> forty years. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="7:37">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:37">37</span></font></b> &ldquo;This is the Moses who said to the sons of Israel, &apos;God will raise up for you a prophet like me from among your brothers.&apos;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A quotation from Deut 18:15."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:38">38</span></font></b> This is the one who was in the congregation in the wilderness with the angel who spoke to him at Mount Sinai, and who <i>[with]</i> our fathers received living oracles to give to us, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:39">39</span></font></b> to whom our fathers were not willing to become obedient, but rejected <i>[him]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and turned <i>[back]</i> in their hearts to Egypt, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:40">40</span></font></b> saying to Aaron, &apos;Make us gods who will go on before us! For this Moses, who led us out from the land of Egypt--we do not know what has happened to him!&apos;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A quotation from Exod 32:1, 23."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:41">41</span></font></b> And they manufactured a calf in those days, and offered up a sacrifice to the idol, and began rejoicing<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The imperfect tense has been translated as ingressive here (&ldquo;began rejoicing&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> in the works of their hands. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:42">42</span></font></b> But God turned away and gave them over to worship the host of heaven, just as it is written in the book of the prophets: &apos;You did not bring offerings and sacrifices to me <i>[for]</i> forty years in the wilderness, <i>[did you]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The negative construction in Greek anticipates a negative answer here, indicated by &ldquo;<i>[did you]</i>.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> house of Israel? <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:43">43</span></font></b> And you took along the tabernacle<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;tent.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> of Moloch and the star of the god<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Some manuscripts have &ldquo;of your god.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Rephan, the images that you made, to worship them, and I will deport you beyond Babylon!&apos;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A quotation from Amos 5:25-27."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="7:44">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:44">44</span></font></b> The tabernacle of the testimony <u>belonged</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;was.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to our fathers in the wilderness, just as the one who spoke to Moses directed <i>[him]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to make it according to the design that he had seen, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:45">45</span></font></b> and which, <i>[after]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;receiving&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> receiving <i>[it]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> in turn, our fathers brought in with Joshua <u>when they dispossessed the</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;in the possession of the.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> nations that God drove out from the presence of our fathers, until the days of David, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:46">46</span></font></b> who found favor in the sight of God and asked to find a habitation for the God of Jacob.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Some manuscripts have &ldquo;for the house of Jacob.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:47">47</span></font></b> But Solomon built a house for him. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:48">48</span></font></b> But the Most High does not live in <i>[houses]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;temples made by human hands&rdquo;; either word (&ldquo;houses&rdquo; or &ldquo;temples&rdquo;) is understood here."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> made by human hands, just as the prophet says, </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="7:49">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:49">49</span></font></b> &apos;Heaven <i>[is]</i> my throne and earth <i>[is]</i> the footstool for my feet. What kind of house will you build for me, says the Lord, or what <i>[is the]</i> place of my rest? <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:50">50</span></font></b> Did not my hand make all these <i>[things]</i>?&apos;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A quotation from Isa 66:1-2."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="7:51">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:51">51</span></font></b> &ldquo;<i>[You]</i> stiff-necked <i>[people]</i> and uncircumcised in hearts and in <i>[your]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> ears! You constantly resist the Holy Spirit! As your fathers <i>[did]</i>, <i>[so]</i> also <i>[do]</i> you! <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:52">52</span></font></b> Which of the prophets did your fathers not persecute? And they killed those who announced beforehand about the coming of the Righteous One, whose betrayers and murderers you have now become, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:53">53</span></font></b> <i>[you]</i> who received the law by directions of angels and have not observed <i>[it]</i>!&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="7:54">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:54">54</span></font></b> Now <i>[when they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;heard&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> heard these <i>[things]</i>, they were infuriated in their hearts and gnashed <i>[their]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> teeth at him. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:55">55</span></font></b> But he, being full of the Holy Spirit, looked intently into heaven <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;looked intently&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> saw the glory of God, and Jesus standing at the right hand of God. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:56">56</span></font></b> And he said, &ldquo;Behold, I see the heavens opened and the Son of Man standing at the right hand of God!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:57">57</span></font></b> But crying out with a loud voice, they stopped their ears and rushed at him with one purpose. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:58">58</span></font></b> And <i>[after they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;had driven&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> had driven <i>[him]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> out of the city, they began to stone<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The imperfect tense has been translated as ingressive here (&ldquo;began stoning&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> <i>[him]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and the witnesses laid aside their cloaks at the feet of a young man named Saul. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:59">59</span></font></b> And they kept on stoning Stephen <i>[as he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[as]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;was calling out&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> was calling out and saying, &ldquo;Lord Jesus, receive my spirit!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:60">60</span></font></b> And falling to <i>[his]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> knees, he cried out with a loud voice, &ldquo;Lord, do not hold this sin against them!&rdquo; And <i>[after he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;said&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said this, he fell asleep.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;he passed away.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="8:1">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:1">8:1</span></font></b> And Saul was agreeing with his murder. Now there happened on that day a great persecution against the church in Jerusalem, and they were all scattered throughout the regions of Judea and Samaria, except the apostles. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:2">2</span></font></b> And devout men buried Stephen and made loud lamentation over him. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:3">3</span></font></b> But Saul was attempting to destroy the church. Entering <u>house after house</u>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;from house&rdquo; <i>[to house]</i>."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> he dragged off both men and women <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;dragged off&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> delivered <i>[them]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to prison. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="8:4">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:4">4</span></font></b> Now those who had been scattered went about proclaiming the good news <i>[of]</i> the word. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:5">5</span></font></b> And Philip came down to the city of Samaria <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;came down&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> began proclaiming<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The imperfect tense has been translated as ingressive here (&ldquo;began proclaiming&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the Christ<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;Messiah.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to them. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:6">6</span></font></b> And the crowds with one mind were paying attention to what was being said by Philip, <i>[as]</i> they heard <i>[him]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and saw the signs that he was performing. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:7">7</span></font></b> For many of those who had unclean spirits, they were coming out <i>[of them]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The words &ldquo;<i>[of them]</i>&rdquo; are supplied in the translation to indicate that the unclean spirits were coming out of the people."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> crying out with a loud voice, and many who were paralyzed and lame were healed. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:8">8</span></font></b> And there was great joy in that city. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="8:9">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:9">9</span></font></b> Now a certain man <u>named</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;by name.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Simon had been in the city practicing magic and astonishing the people of Samaria, saying he was someone great. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:10">10</span></font></b> They were all paying attention to <u>him</u>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;whom.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> from the least to the greatest, saying, &ldquo;This man is the power of God that is called &apos;Great.&apos;&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:11">11</span></font></b> And they were paying attention to him because for a long time he had astonished them with <i>[his]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> magic. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:12">12</span></font></b> But when they believed Philip <i>[as he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[as]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;was proclaiming the good news&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> was proclaiming the good news about the kingdom of God and the name of Jesus Christ, both men and women were being baptized. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:13">13</span></font></b> And Simon himself also believed, and <i>[after he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;was baptized&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> was baptized he was <u>keeping close company with</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;attaching himself to.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Philip. And <i>[when he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;saw&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> saw the signs and great miracles that were taking place, he was astonished. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="8:14">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:14">14</span></font></b> Now <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;heard&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the apostles in Jerusalem heard that Samaria had accepted the word of God, they sent Peter and John to them, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:15">15</span></font></b> who went down <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;went down&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> prayed for them so that they would receive the Holy Spirit. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:16">16</span></font></b> (For he had not yet fallen on any of them, <u>but they had only been baptized</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;but they were only having been baptized.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> in the name of the Lord Jesus.) <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:17">17</span></font></b> Then they placed <i>[their]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> hands on them and they received the Holy Spirit. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="8:18">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:18">18</span></font></b> Now Simon, <i>[when he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;saw&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> saw that the Spirit was given through the laying on of the apostles&apos; hands, offered them money, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:19">19</span></font></b> saying, &ldquo;Give to me also this power, so that whomever I place <i>[my]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> hands on may receive the Holy Spirit!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:20">20</span></font></b> But Peter said to him, &ldquo;May your silver <u>be destroyed along with you</u>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;be for destruction with you.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> because you thought <u>you could acquire</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;to acquire.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the gift of God by means of money! <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:21">21</span></font></b> <u>You have no</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;there is for you no.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> part or share in this matter, because your heart is not right before God. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:22">22</span></font></b> Therefore repent of this wickedness of yours, and ask the Lord if perhaps the intent of your heart may be forgiven you!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:23">23</span></font></b> For I see you are in <u>a state of bitter envy</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the gall of bitterness.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and <u>bound by unrighteousness</u>.&rdquo;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the fetter of unrighteousness.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:24">24</span></font></b> But Simon answered <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;answered&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said, &ldquo;You pray to the Lord for me so that nothing of what you have said will come upon me.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:25">25</span></font></b> So <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;had solemnly testified&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> they had solemnly testified and spoken the word of the Lord, they turned back toward Jerusalem, and were proclaiming the good news <i>[to]</i> many villages of the Samaritans. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="8:26">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:26">26</span></font></b> Now an angel of the Lord spoke to Philip, saying, &ldquo;Get up and go toward the south<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;go about noon.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> on the road that goes down from Jerusalem to Gaza.&rdquo; (This is a desert <i>[road]</i>.) <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:27">27</span></font></b> And he got up <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;got up&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> went, and behold, <i>[there was]</i> a man, an Ethiopian eunuch (a court official of Candace,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;the Candace&rdquo; (the title of the queen of Ethiopia)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> queen of the Ethiopians, who was over all her treasury) who had come to worship in Jerusalem <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:28">28</span></font></b> and was returning and sitting in his chariot, and reading aloud the prophet Isaiah. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:29">29</span></font></b> And the Spirit said to Philip, &ldquo;Approach and join this chariot.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:30">30</span></font></b> So Philip ran up to <i>[it]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;ran up to&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> heard him reading aloud Isaiah the prophet and said, &ldquo;So then, do you understand what you are reading?&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:31">31</span></font></b> And he said, &ldquo;So how could I, unless someone will guide me?&rdquo; And he invited Philip to come up <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;come up&rdquo;) has been translated as an infinitive."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> sit with him. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:32">32</span></font></b> Now the passage of scripture that he was reading aloud was this: &ldquo;He was led like a sheep to the slaughter, and like a lamb before its shearer <i>[is]</i> silent, so he did not open his mouth. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:33">33</span></font></b> In his<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> humiliation justice was taken from him. Who can describe his <u>descendants</u>?<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or perhaps &ldquo;family history&rdquo;; literally &ldquo;generation.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> For his life was taken away from the earth.&rdquo;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A quotation from Isa 53:7-8."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="8:34">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:34">34</span></font></b> And the eunuch answered <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;answered&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said to Philip, &ldquo;I ask you, about whom does the prophet say this--about himself or about someone else?&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:35">35</span></font></b> So Philip opened his mouth and beginning from this scripture, proclaimed the good news to him <i>[about]</i> Jesus. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:36">36</span></font></b> And as they were traveling down the road, they came to some water. And the eunuch said, &ldquo;Look! Water! What prevents me from being baptized?&rdquo;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A few later manuscripts add v. 37, with minor variations: &ldquo;He said to him, &apos;If you believe with your whole heart, you may.&apos; And he answered and said, &apos;I believe that Jesus Christ is the Son of God.&apos;&rdquo; The verse is almost certainly not an original part of the text of Acts."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:38">38</span></font></b> And he ordered the chariot to stop, and they both went down into the water--Philip and the eunuch--and he baptized him. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:39">39</span></font></b> And when they came up out of the water, the Spirit of the Lord carried Philip away, and the eunuch did not see him any longer, for he went on his way rejoicing. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:40">40</span></font></b> But Philip found himself at Azotus, and <i>[as he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[as]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;passed through&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> passed through, he proclaimed the good news <i>[to]</i> all the towns until he came to Caesarea. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="9:1">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:1">9:1</span></font></b> But Saul, still breathing threats and murder against the disciples of the Lord, went to the high priest <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:2">2</span></font></b> <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the participle in the previous verse (&ldquo;went to&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> asked for letters from him to the synagogues in Damascus, so that if he found any who were of the Way, both men and women, he could bring <i>[them]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> tied up<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or figuratively &ldquo;bring <i>[them]</i> under arrest.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to Jerusalem. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:3">3</span></font></b> Now as <i>[he]</i> proceeded, it happened that <i>[when]</i> he approached Damascus, suddenly a light from heaven flashed around him. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:4">4</span></font></b> And falling to the ground, he heard a voice saying to him, &ldquo;Saul, Saul, why are you persecuting me?&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:5">5</span></font></b> So he said, &ldquo;Who are you, Lord?&rdquo; And he <i>[said]</i>, &ldquo;I am Jesus, whom you are persecuting! <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:6">6</span></font></b> But get up and enter into the city, and it will be told to you <u>what you must do</u>.&rdquo;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;what thing it is necessary <i>[that]</i> you do.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:7">7</span></font></b> (Now the men who were traveling together with him stood speechless, <i>[because they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[because]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;heard&rdquo;) which is understood as causal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> heard the voice but saw no one.) <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:8">8</span></font></b> So Saul got up from the ground, but <i>[although]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[although]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;were open&rdquo;) which is understood as concessive."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> his eyes were open he could see nothing. And leading him by the hand, they brought <i>[him]</i> into Damascus. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:9">9</span></font></b> And he was <u>unable to see</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;not seeing.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> <i>[for]</i> three days, and he did not eat or drink. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="9:10">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:10">10</span></font></b> Now there was a certain disciple in Damascus <u>named</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;by name.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Ananias, and the Lord said to him in a vision, &ldquo;Ananias!&rdquo; And he said, &ldquo;Behold, <i>[here]</i> I <i>[am]</i>, Lord!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:11">11</span></font></b> And the Lord <i>[said]</i> to him, &ldquo;Get up, go to the street called &apos;Straight&apos; and in the house of Judas look for <u>a man named Saul from Tarsus</u>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;Saul by name of Tarsus.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> For behold, he is praying, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:12">12</span></font></b> and he has seen in a vision a man <u>named</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;by name.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Ananias coming in and placing hands<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Some manuscripts have &ldquo;placing his hands.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> on him so that he may regain <i>[his]</i> sight.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:13">13</span></font></b> But Ananias replied, &ldquo;Lord, I have heard from many <i>[people]</i> about this man, how much harm he has done to your saints in Jerusalem, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:14">14</span></font></b> and here he has authority from the chief priests to tie up<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or figuratively &ldquo;to arrest&rdquo; or &ldquo;to imprison.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> all who call upon your name!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:15">15</span></font></b> But the Lord said to him, &ldquo;Go, because this man is my chosen instrument to carry my name before Gentiles<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The same Greek word can be translated &ldquo;nations&rdquo; or &ldquo;Gentiles&rdquo; depending on the context."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and kings and the sons of Israel. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:16">16</span></font></b> For I will show him how much he must suffer for the sake of my name.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:17">17</span></font></b> So Ananias departed and entered into the house, and placing <i>[his]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> hands on him, he said, &ldquo;Brother Saul, the Lord Jesus, who appeared to you on the road by which you came, has sent me so that you may regain <i>[your]</i> sight and be filled with the Holy Spirit.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:18">18</span></font></b> And immediately <i>[something]</i> like scales fell from his eyes and he regained <i>[his]</i> sight and got up <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;got up&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> was baptized, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:19">19</span></font></b> and <i>[after]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;taking&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> taking food, he regained his strength. And he was with the disciples in Damascus several days. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="9:20">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:20">20</span></font></b> And immediately he began proclaiming<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The imperfect tense has been translated as ingressive here (&ldquo;began proclaiming&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Jesus in the synagogues: &ldquo;This one is the Son of God!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:21">21</span></font></b> And all who heard <i>[him]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> were amazed, and were saying, &ldquo;Is this not the one who was wreaking havoc in Jerusalem <i>[on]</i> those who call upon this name, and had come here for this <i>[reason]</i>, that he could bring them tied up<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or figuratively &ldquo;bring them under arrest.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to the chief priests?&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:22">22</span></font></b> But Saul was increasing in strength even more, and was confounding the Jews who lived in Damascus <i>[by]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[by]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;proving&rdquo;) which is understood as means."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> proving that this one is the Christ.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;Messiah.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="9:23">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:23">23</span></font></b> And when many days had elapsed, the Jews plotted to do away with him. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:24">24</span></font></b> But their plot became known to Saul, and they were also watching the gates both day and night so that they could do away with him. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:25">25</span></font></b> But his disciples took <i>[him]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> at night <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;took&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> let him down through the wall <i>[by]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[by]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;lowering&rdquo;) which is understood as means."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> lowering <i>[him]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> in a basket. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="9:26">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:26">26</span></font></b> And <i>[when he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;arrived&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> arrived in Jerusalem, he was attempting to associate with the disciples, and they were all afraid of him, <i>[because they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[because]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;believe&rdquo;) which is understood as causal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> did not believe that he was a disciple. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:27">27</span></font></b> But Barnabas took him <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;took&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> brought <i>[him]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to the apostles and related to them how he had seen the Lord on the road and that he had spoken to him, and how in Damascus he had spoken boldly in the name of Jesus. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:28">28</span></font></b> And he was going in and going out among them in Jerusalem, speaking boldly in the name of the Lord. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:29">29</span></font></b> And he was speaking and debating with the <u>Greek-speaking Jews</u>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;Hellenists.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> but they were trying to do away with him. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:30">30</span></font></b> And <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;found out&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the brothers found out, they brought him down to Caesarea and sent him away to Tarsus. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="9:31">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:31">31</span></font></b> Then the church throughout all of Judea and Galilee and Samaria had peace, being strengthened. And living in the fear of the Lord and the encouragement of the Holy Spirit, it was increasing <i>[in numbers]</i>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The words &ldquo;<i>[in numbers]</i>&rdquo; are not in the Greek text but are implied."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="9:32">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:32">32</span></font></b> Now it happened that <i>[as]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[as]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;was traveling&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Peter was traveling through all <i>[the places]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The words &ldquo;<i>[the places]</i>&rdquo; are not in the Greek text but are implied."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> <i>[he]</i> also came down to the saints who lived <i>[in]</i> Lydda. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:33">33</span></font></b> And he found there a certain man <u>named</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;by name.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Aeneas who was paralyzed, who had been lying on a mat<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;mattress.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> for eight years. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:34">34</span></font></b> And Peter said to him, &ldquo;Aeneas, Jesus Christ heals you! Get up and make your bed yourself!&rdquo; And immediately he got up. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:35">35</span></font></b> And all those who lived <i>[in]</i> Lydda and Sharon saw him, who <i>[all]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[all]</i>&rdquo; is supplied to indicate the relative pronoun is plural."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> indeed turned to the Lord. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="9:36">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:36">36</span></font></b> Now in Joppa there was a certain female disciple <u>named</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;by name.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Tabitha (which translated means &ldquo;Dorcas&rdquo;).<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="&ldquo;Dorcas&rdquo; is the Greek translation of the Aramaic name &ldquo;Tabitha&rdquo; which means &ldquo;deer&rdquo; or &ldquo;gazelle.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> She was full of good deeds and charitable giving which she was constantly doing.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the imperfect verb is translated as a customary imperfect (&ldquo;was constantly doing&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:37">37</span></font></b> Now it happened that in those days <i>[after]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;becoming sick&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> becoming sick, she died. And <i>[after]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;washing&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> washing <i>[her]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> they placed her in an upstairs room. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:38">38</span></font></b> And <i>[because]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[because]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;was&rdquo;) which is understood as causal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Lydda was near Joppa, the disciples, <i>[when they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;heard&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> heard that Peter was in <u>Lydda</u>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;in it.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> sent two men to him, urging, &ldquo;Do not delay to come to us!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:39">39</span></font></b> So Peter got up <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;got up&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> accompanied them. <i>[When he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;arrived&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> arrived, they brought <i>[him]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> up to the upstairs room, and all the widows came to him, weeping and showing <i>[him]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> tunics and <i>[other]</i> clothing that Dorcas used to make <i>[while she]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[while]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;was&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> was with them. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:40">40</span></font></b> But Peter sent <i>[them]</i> all outside, and, falling to <i>[his]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> knees, he prayed. And turning toward the body, he said, &ldquo;Tabitha, get up!&rdquo; And she opened her eyes, and <i>[when she]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;saw&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> saw Peter, she sat up. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:41">41</span></font></b> And he gave her <i>[his]</i> hand <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;gave&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> raised her up. And he called the saints and the widows <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;called&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> presented her alive. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:42">42</span></font></b> And it became known throughout all Joppa, and many believed in the Lord. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:43">43</span></font></b> And it happened that <i>[he]</i> stayed many days in Joppa with a certain Simon, a tanner.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;with a certain Simon Berseus&rdquo;; most modern English versions treat the word as Simon&apos;s profession (&ldquo;Simon the tanner&rdquo;), but the word may actually be a surname (&ldquo;Simon Berseus&rdquo; or &ldquo;Simon Tanner&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="10:1">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:1">10:1</span></font></b> Now <i>[there was]</i> a certain man in Caesarea <u>named</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;by name.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Cornelius, a centurion of what was called the Italian Cohort, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:2">2</span></font></b> devout and fearing God together with all his household, doing many charitable deeds for the people and praying to God <u>continually</u>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;through everything.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:3">3</span></font></b> About the ninth hour of the day, he saw clearly in a vision an angel of God coming to him and saying to him, &ldquo;Cornelius.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:4">4</span></font></b> And he stared at him and became terrified <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;became&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said, &ldquo;What is <i>[it]</i>, Lord?&rdquo; And he said to him, &ldquo;Your prayers and your charitable deeds have gone up for a memorial offering before God. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:5">5</span></font></b> And now, send men to Joppa and summon a certain Simon, who is also called Peter. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:6">6</span></font></b> This man is staying as a guest with a certain Simon, a tanner,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;with a certain Simon Berseus&rdquo;; most modern English versions treat the word as Simon&apos;s profession (&ldquo;Simon the tanner&rdquo;), but the word may actually be a surname (&ldquo;Simon Berseus&rdquo; or &ldquo;Simon Tanner&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> whose house is by the sea.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:7">7</span></font></b> And when the angel who spoke to him departed, he summoned two of the household slaves and a devout soldier from those who attended him, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:8">8</span></font></b> and <i>[after he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;had explained&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> had explained everything to them, he sent them to Joppa. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="10:9">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:9">9</span></font></b> And the next day, <i>[as]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[as]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;were on their way&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> they were on their way and approaching the city, Peter went up on the housetop to pray <i>[at]</i> about the sixth hour. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:10">10</span></font></b> And he became hungry and wanted to eat. But <i>[while]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[while]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;were preparing&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> they were preparing <i>[the food]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> a trance came over him. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:11">11</span></font></b> And he saw heaven opened and an object something like a large sheet coming down, being let down to the earth by its four corners, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:12">12</span></font></b> in which were all the four-footed animals and reptiles of the earth and birds of the sky. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:13">13</span></font></b> And a voice came to him, &ldquo;Get up, Peter, slaughter and eat!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:14">14</span></font></b> But Peter said, &ldquo;Certainly not, Lord! For I have never eaten anything common and unclean!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:15">15</span></font></b> And the voice <i>[came]</i> again to him for the second time: &ldquo;<i>[The things]</i> which God has made clean, you must not consider unclean!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:16">16</span></font></b> And this happened three times, and immediately the object was taken up into heaven. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="10:17">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:17">17</span></font></b> Now while Peter was greatly perplexed within himself <i>[as to]</i> what the vision that he had seen might be, behold, the men who had been sent by Cornelius, having found the house of Simon by asking around, stood at the gate. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:18">18</span></font></b> And they called out <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;called out&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> asked if Simon who was also called Peter was staying there as a guest. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:19">19</span></font></b> And <i>[while]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[while]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;was reflecting&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Peter was reflecting about the vision, the Spirit said to him, &ldquo;Behold, men<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Some manuscripts have &ldquo;three men.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> are looking for you. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:20">20</span></font></b> But get up, go down, and go with them--not hesitating at all, because I have sent them.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:21">21</span></font></b> So Peter went down to the men <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;went down&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said, &ldquo;Behold, I am <i>[he]</i> whom you are looking for! What <i>[is]</i> the reason for which you have come?&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:22">22</span></font></b> And they said, &ldquo;Cornelius, a centurion, a righteous and God-fearing man--and well spoken of by the whole nation of the Jews--was directed by a holy angel to summon you to his house and to hear words from you.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:23">23</span></font></b> So he invited them in <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;invited ... in&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> entertained them as guests, and on the next day he got up <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;got up&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> went away with them. And some of the brothers from Joppa accompanied him. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:24">24</span></font></b> And on the next day he entered into Caesarea. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="10:25">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:25">25</span></font></b> So it happened that when Peter entered, Cornelius met him, fell at <i>[his]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> feet, <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;fell&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> worshiped <i>[him]</i>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:26">26</span></font></b> But Peter helped him up, saying, &ldquo;Get up! I myself am also a man!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:27">27</span></font></b> And <i>[as he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[as]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;conversed with&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> conversed with him, he went in and found many <i>[people]</i> gathered. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:28">28</span></font></b> And he said to them, &ldquo;You know that it is forbidden for a Jewish man to associate with or to approach a foreigner. And to me God has shown <i>[that]</i> I should call no man common or unclean. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:29">29</span></font></b> Therefore--and without raising any objection--I came <i>[when I]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;was sent for&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> was sent for. So I ask for what reason you sent for me.&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="10:30">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:30">30</span></font></b> And Cornelius said, &ldquo;<u>Four days ago at this hour</u>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;from the fourth day until this hour.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> <i>[the]</i> ninth, I was praying in my house. And behold, a man in shining clothing stood before me <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:31">31</span></font></b> and said, &apos;Cornelius, your prayer has been heard, and your charitable deeds have been remembered before God. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:32">32</span></font></b> Therefore send to Joppa and summon Simon who is also called Peter. This man is staying as a guest in the house of Simon, a tanner,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;of Simon Berseus&rdquo;; most modern English versions treat the word as Simon&apos;s profession (&ldquo;Simon the tanner&rdquo;), but the word may actually be a surname (&ldquo;Simon Berseus&rdquo; or &ldquo;Simon Tanner&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> by the sea. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:33">33</span></font></b> Therefore I sent for you at once, and you <u>were kind enough to come</u>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;have done rightly coming.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> So now we all are present before God to hear all the things that have been commanded to you by the Lord.&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="10:34">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:34">34</span></font></b> So Peter opened <i>[his]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> mouth <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;opened&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said, &ldquo;In truth I understand that God is not one who shows partiality, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:35">35</span></font></b> but in every nation the one who fears him and who does what is right is acceptable to him. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:36">36</span></font></b> <i>[As for]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The words &ldquo;<i>[As for]</i>&rdquo; are not in the Greek text, but are supplied in the translation in keeping with English style."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the message that he sent to the sons of Israel, proclaiming the good news of peace through Jesus Christ--this one is Lord of all-- <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:37">37</span></font></b> you know the thing that happened throughout all Judea, beginning from Galilee, after the baptism that John proclaimed: <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:38">38</span></font></b> Jesus of Nazareth--how God anointed him with the Holy Spirit and with power, who went about doing good and healing all who were oppressed by the devil, because God was with him. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:39">39</span></font></b> And we <i>[are]</i> witnesses of all <i>[the things]</i> that he did both in the land of the Judeans and in Jerusalem, whom they also executed <i>[by]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[by]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;hanging&rdquo;) which is understood as means."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> hanging <i>[him]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> on a tree. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:40">40</span></font></b> God raised this one up on the third day and granted <i>[that]</i> he should become visible, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:41">41</span></font></b> not to all the people but to us who had been chosen beforehand by God <i>[as]</i> witnesses, who ate and drank with him after he rose from the dead. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:42">42</span></font></b> And he commanded us to preach to the people and to testify solemnly that this one is the one appointed<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;one who is designated.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> by God <i>[as]</i> judge of the living and of the dead. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:43">43</span></font></b> To this one all the prophets testify, <i>[that]</i> through his name everyone who believes in him receives forgiveness of sins.&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="10:44">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:44">44</span></font></b> <i>[While]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[while]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;was ... speaking&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Peter was still speaking these words, the Holy Spirit fell on all those who were listening to the message. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:45">45</span></font></b> And those believers from the circumcision who had accompanied Peter were astonished that the gift of the Holy Spirit had been poured out even on the Gentiles, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:46">46</span></font></b> for they heard them speaking in tongues and glorifying God. Then Peter said, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:47">47</span></font></b> &ldquo;Surely no one can withhold the water for these <i>[people]</i> to be baptized, who have received the Holy Spirit as we also did!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:48">48</span></font></b> So he ordered <i>[that]</i> they be baptized in the name of Jesus Christ. Then they asked him to stay for several days. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="11:1">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="11:1">11:1</span></font></b> Now the apostles and the brothers who were throughout Judea heard that the Gentiles also had accepted the word<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;message.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> of God. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="11:2">2</span></font></b> So when Peter went up to Jerusalem, those of the circumcision took issue with him, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="11:3">3</span></font></b> saying, &ldquo;You went to men <u>who were uncircumcised</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;who had uncircumcision."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and ate with them!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="11:4">4</span></font></b> But Peter began <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;began&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> explained <i>[it]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to them in an orderly sequence, saying, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="11:5">5</span></font></b> &ldquo;I was in the city of Joppa praying, and in a trance I saw a vision--an object something like a large sheet coming down, being let down from heaven by its four corners, and it came to me. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="11:6">6</span></font></b> <i>[As I]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[as]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;looked intently&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> looked intently into it, I was considering <i>[it]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and I saw the four-footed animals of the earth and the wild animals and the reptiles and the birds of the sky. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="11:7">7</span></font></b> And I also heard a voice saying to me, &apos;Get up, Peter, slaughter and eat!&apos; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="11:8">8</span></font></b> But I said, &apos;Certainly not, Lord! For nothing common or unclean has ever entered into my mouth!&apos; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="11:9">9</span></font></b> But the voice replied from heaven for the second time, &apos;<i>[The things]</i> which God has made clean, you must not consider unclean!&apos; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="11:10">10</span></font></b> And this happened three times, and everything was pulled up into heaven again. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="11:11">11</span></font></b> And behold, at once three men who had been sent to me from Caesarea approached the house in which we were <i>[staying]</i>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the word &ldquo;staying&rdquo; is not in the Greek text but is implied."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="11:12">12</span></font></b> And the Spirit told me to accompany them, not hesitating <i>[at all]</i>. So these six brothers also went with me, and we entered into the man&apos;s house. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="11:13">13</span></font></b> And he reported to us how he had seen the angel standing in his house and saying, &apos;Send to Joppa and summon Simon, who is also called Peter, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="11:14">14</span></font></b> who will speak words to you by which you will be saved, you and all your household.&apos; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="11:15">15</span></font></b> And <i>[as]</i> I was beginning to speak, the Holy Spirit fell on them, just as also on us at the beginning. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="11:16">16</span></font></b> And I remembered the word of the Lord, how he said, &apos;John baptized with water, but you will be baptized with the Holy Spirit.&apos;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="An allusion to Acts 1:5."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="11:17">17</span></font></b> Therefore if God gave them the same gift as also to us <i>[when we]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;believed&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> believed in the Lord Jesus Christ, who was I <i>[to be]</i> able to hinder God?&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="11:18">18</span></font></b> And <i>[when they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;heard&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> heard these <i>[things]</i>, they became silent<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the aorist verb is translated as ingressive (&ldquo;became silent&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and praised God, saying, &ldquo;Then God has granted the repentance <i>[leading]</i> to life to the Gentiles also!&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="11:19">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="11:19">19</span></font></b> Now those who had been scattered because of the persecution that took place over Stephen traveled as far as Phoenicia and Cyprus and Antioch, proclaiming the message to no one except Jews alone. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="11:20">20</span></font></b> But some of them were men from Cyprus and Cyrene, who, <i>[when they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;came&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> came to Antioch, began to speak<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The imperfect tense has been translated as ingressive here (&ldquo;began to speak&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to the Hellenists<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here this term could refer to (1) Greek-speaking Jews or (2) Greek-speaking non-Jews (i.e., Gentiles)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> also, proclaiming the good news about the Lord Jesus. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="11:21">21</span></font></b> And the hand of the Lord was with them, and a large number who believed turned to the Lord. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="11:22">22</span></font></b> <u>And the report came to the attention</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;and the report was heard in the ears.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> of the church that was in Jerusalem about them, and they sent out Barnabas as far as<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Some manuscripts have &ldquo;to go as far as.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Antioch, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="11:23">23</span></font></b> who, <i>[when he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;arrived&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> arrived and saw the grace of God, rejoiced and encouraged <i>[them]</i> all to remain true to the Lord with <u>devoted hearts</u>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;purpose of heart.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="11:24">24</span></font></b> because he was a good man and full of the Holy Spirit and of faith. And a large number were added<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;were brought.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to the Lord. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="11:25">25</span></font></b> So he departed for Tarsus to look for Saul. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="11:26">26</span></font></b> And <i>[when he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;found&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> found <i>[him]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> he brought <i>[him]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to Antioch. And it happened to them also <i>[that they]</i> met together <i>[for]</i> a whole year with the church and taught a large number <i>[of people]</i>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The words &ldquo;<i>[of people]</i>&rdquo; are not in the Greek text but are implied."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> And in Antioch the disciples were first called Christians. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="11:27">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="11:27">27</span></font></b> Now in those days prophets came down from Jerusalem to Antioch. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="11:28">28</span></font></b> And one of them <u>named</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;by name.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Agabus stood up <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;stood up&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> indicated by the Spirit <i>[that]</i> a great famine was about to come over the whole inhabited earth (which took place in the time of Claudius). <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="11:29">29</span></font></b> So from the disciples, <u>according to their ability to give</u>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;to the degree that anyone was prospering.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> each one of them determined to send <i>[financial aid]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> for support to the brothers who lived in Judea, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="11:30">30</span></font></b> which they also did, sending <i>[the aid]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to the elders by the hand of Barnabas and Saul. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="12:1">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:1">12:1</span></font></b> Now at that time, Herod the king laid hands on some of those from the church to harm <i>[them]</i>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:2">2</span></font></b> So he executed James the brother of John with a sword. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:3">3</span></font></b> And <i>[when he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;saw&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> saw that it was pleasing to the Jews, he proceeded to arrest Peter also. (<u>Now this was during the feast</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;now these were the days.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> of Unleavened Bread.) <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:4">4</span></font></b> <i>[After he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;had arrested&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> had arrested <u>him</u>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;whom.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> he also put <i>[him]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> in prison, handing <i>[him]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> over to four squads of soldiers to guard him, intending to bring him <u>out for public trial</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;to the people.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> after the Passover. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:5">5</span></font></b> Thus Peter was kept in the prison, but prayer was fervently being made to God by the church for him. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="12:6">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:6">6</span></font></b> Now when Herod was about to bring him <i>[out]</i>, on that <i>[very]</i> night Peter was sleeping between two soldiers, bound with two chains, and guards before the door were watching the prison. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:7">7</span></font></b> And behold, an angel of the Lord stood near <i>[him]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and a light shone in the prison cell. And striking Peter&apos;s side, he woke him up, saying, &ldquo;Get up <u>quickly</u>!&rdquo;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;with quickness.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> And his chains fell off of <i>[his]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> hands. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:8">8</span></font></b> And the angel said to him, &ldquo;Gird yourself and put on your sandals!&rdquo; And he did so. And he said to him, &ldquo;Wrap your cloak around you and follow me!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:9">9</span></font></b> And he went out <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;went out&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> was following <i>[him]</i>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> And he did not know that what was being done by the angel was real, but was thinking <i>[he]</i> was seeing a vision. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:10">10</span></font></b> And <i>[after they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;had passed&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> had passed the first and second guard, they came to the iron gate that leads to the city, which opened for them by itself, and they went out <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;went out&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> went forward <i>[along]</i> one narrow street, and at once the angel departed from him. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="12:11">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:11">11</span></font></b> And <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;came&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Peter came to himself, he said, &ldquo;Now I know truly that the Lord has sent out his angel and rescued me from the hand of Herod and all <u>that the Jewish people expected</u>!&rdquo;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the expectation of the people of the Jews.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:12">12</span></font></b> And <i>[when he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;realized&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> realized <i>[this]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> he went to the house of Mary, the mother of John (who is also called Mark), where many <i>[people]</i> were gathered together and were praying. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:13">13</span></font></b> And <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;knocked&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> he knocked at the door of the gateway, a female slave <u>named</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;by name.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Rhoda came up to answer. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:14">14</span></font></b> And recognizing Peter&apos;s voice, because of <i>[her]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> joy she did not open the gate, but ran in <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;ran in&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> announced <i>[that]</i> Peter was standing at the gate. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:15">15</span></font></b> But they said to her, &ldquo;You are out of your mind!&rdquo; But she kept insisting<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="This imperfect verb is translated as an iterative imperfect (&ldquo;kept insisting&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> it was so. And they kept saying,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="This imperfect verb is translated as an iterative imperfect (&ldquo;kept saying&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> &ldquo;It is his angel!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:16">16</span></font></b> But Peter was continuing to knock, and <i>[when they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;opened&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> opened <i>[the door]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> they saw him and were astonished. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:17">17</span></font></b> But motioning to them with <i>[his]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> hand to be silent, he related to them how the Lord had brought him out of the prison. And he said, &ldquo;Report these <i>[things]</i> to James and to the brothers,&rdquo; and he departed <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;departed&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> went to another place. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="12:18">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:18">18</span></font></b> Now <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;came&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> day came, there was not a little commotion among the soldiers <i>[as to]</i> what then had become of Peter. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:19">19</span></font></b> And <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;had searched for&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Herod had searched for him and did not find <i>[him]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> he questioned the guards <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;questioned&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> ordered <i>[that they]</i> be led away to execution. And he came down from Judea to Caesarea <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;came down&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> stayed <i>[there]</i>. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="12:20">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:20">20</span></font></b> Now he was very angry with the Tyrians and Sidonians. So they came to him with one purpose, and <i>[after]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;persuading&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> persuading Blastus, <u>the king&apos;s chamberlain</u>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the <i>[one]</i> over the bedroom of the king.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> they asked for peace, because their country was supported with food from the king&apos;s country. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:21">21</span></font></b> So on an appointed day Herod, <i>[after]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;putting on&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> putting on royal clothing and sitting down on the judgment seat, began to deliver a public address to them. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:22">22</span></font></b> But the people began to call out loudly,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The imperfect tense has been translated as ingressive here (&ldquo;began to call out loudly&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> &ldquo;The voice of a god and not of a man!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:23">23</span></font></b> And immediately an angel of the Lord struck him down <u>because</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;in return for which.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> he did not give the glory to God. And he was eaten by worms <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;was&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> died. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:24">24</span></font></b> But the word of God kept on increasing<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="This imperfect verb has been translated as customary (&ldquo;kept on increasing&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and multiplying. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="12:25">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:25">25</span></font></b> So Barnabas and Saul returned to<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Some manuscripts read &ldquo;from.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Jerusalem <i>[when they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;had completed&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> had completed <i>[their]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> service, having taken along with <i>[them]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> John (who is also called Mark). </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="13:1">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:1">13:1</span></font></b> Now there were prophets and teachers in Antioch in the church that was there: Barnabas, and Simeon (who was called Niger), and Lucius the Cyrenian, and Manaen (a close friend of Herod the tetrarch), and Saul. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:2">2</span></font></b> And <i>[while]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[while]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;were serving&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> they were serving the Lord and fasting, the Holy Spirit said, &ldquo;Set apart now for me Barnabas and Saul for the work to which I have called them.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:3">3</span></font></b> Then, <i>[after they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;had fasted&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> had fasted and prayed and placed <i>[their]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> hands on them, they sent <i>[them]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> away. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="13:4">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:4">4</span></font></b> Therefore, sent out by the Holy Spirit, they came down to Seleucia, and from there they sailed away to Cyprus. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:5">5</span></font></b> And <i>[when they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;came&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> came to Salamis, they began to proclaim the word of God in the synagogues of the Jews. And they also had John <i>[as]</i> assistant. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:6">6</span></font></b> And <i>[when they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;had crossed over&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> had crossed over the whole island as far as Paphos, they found a certain man, a magician, a Jewish false prophet whose name <i>[was]</i> Bar-Jesus, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:7">7</span></font></b> who was with the proconsul Sergius Paulus, an intelligent man. This man summoned Barnabas and Saul <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;summoned&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> wished to hear the word of God. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:8">8</span></font></b> But Elymas the magician (for his name is translated in this way) opposed them, attempting to turn the proconsul away from the faith. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:9">9</span></font></b> But Saul (also called Paul), filled with the Holy Spirit, looked intently at him <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:10">10</span></font></b> <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the participle in the previous verse (&ldquo;looked intently at&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said, &ldquo;O <i>[you who are]</i> full of all deceit and of all unscrupulousness, <i>[you]</i> son of the devil, <i>[you]</i> enemy of all righteousness! Will you not stop making crooked the straight paths of the Lord! <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:11">11</span></font></b> And now behold, the hand of the Lord <i>[is]</i> against you, and you will be blind, not seeing the sun <u>for a while</u>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;until the time.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> And immediately mist and darkness fell over him, and he was going around looking for <i>[people]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="In Greek the direct object (&ldquo;people&rdquo;) is understood and must be supplied in the English translation; since the following noun is plural, &ldquo;people&rdquo; rather than &ldquo;someone&rdquo; is used here."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to lead <i>[him]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> by the hand. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:12">12</span></font></b> Then <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;saw&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the proconsul saw what had happened, he believed, <i>[because he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[because]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;was astounded&rdquo;) which is understood as causal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> was astounded at the teaching about<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;about&rdquo; reflects an objective genitive (&ldquo;the Lord&rdquo; is the object of the teaching)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the Lord. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="13:13">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:13">13</span></font></b> Now <u>Paul and his companions</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;those around Paul.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> put out to sea from Paphos <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;put out to sea&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> came to Perga in Pamphylia, but John departed from them <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;departed&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> returned to Jerusalem. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:14">14</span></font></b> And they went on from Perga <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;went on&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> arrived at Pisidian Antioch. And they entered into the synagogue on the day of the Sabbath <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;entered&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> sat down. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:15">15</span></font></b> So after the reading from the law and the prophets, the rulers of the synagogue sent <i>[word]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to them, saying, &ldquo;Men <i>[and]</i> brothers, if there is any message of exhortation by you for the people, say <i>[it]</i>.&rdquo;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="13:16">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:16">16</span></font></b> So Paul stood up,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the participle (&ldquo;stood up&rdquo;) is translated as a finite verb because of English style."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and motioning with <i>[his]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> hand, he said, &ldquo;Israelite men, and those who fear God, listen! <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:17">17</span></font></b> The God of this people Israel chose our fathers and exalted the people during <i>[their]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> stay in the land of Egypt, and with uplifted arm he led them out of it. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:18">18</span></font></b> And for a period of time <i>[of]</i> about forty years, he put up with them in the wilderness. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:19">19</span></font></b> And <i>[after]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;destroying&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> destroying seven nations in the land of Canaan, he gave their land <i>[to his people]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The words &ldquo;<i>[to his people]</i>&rdquo; are supplied as a clarification of who received the land."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> as an inheritance. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:20">20</span></font></b> <i>[This took]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The words &ldquo;<i>[This took]</i>&rdquo; are not in the Greek text but are supplied in keeping with English style."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> about four hundred and fifty years. And after these <i>[things]</i>, he gave <i>[them]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the indirect object &ldquo;<i>[them]</i>&rdquo; is not in the Greek text but is implied."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> judges until Samuel the prophet. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:21">21</span></font></b> And then they asked for a king, and God gave them Saul son of Kish, a man from the tribe of Benjamin, <i>[for]</i> forty years. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:22">22</span></font></b> And <i>[after]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;removing&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> removing him, he raised up David for their king, about whom he also said, testifying, &apos;I have found David the <i>[son]</i> of Jesse <i>[to be]</i> a man in accordance with my heart, who will carry out all my will.&apos;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A quotation from 1 Sam 13:14."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:23">23</span></font></b> From the descendants of this man, according to <i>[his]</i> promise, God brought to Israel a Savior, Jesus. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:24">24</span></font></b> Before <u>his coming</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the presence of his coming.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> John had publicly proclaimed<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the participle (&ldquo;had publicly proclaimed&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb in keeping with English style."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> a baptism of repentance to all the people of Israel. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:25">25</span></font></b> But while John was completing <i>[his]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> mission, he said, &apos;What do you suppose me to be? I am not <i>[he]</i>! But behold, one is coming after me of whom I am not worthy to untie the sandals of <i>[his]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> feet!&apos; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="13:26">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:26">26</span></font></b> &ldquo;Men <i>[and]</i> brothers, sons of the family of Abraham and those among you who fear God--to us the message of this salvation has been sent! <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:27">27</span></font></b> For those who live in Jerusalem and their rulers, <i>[because they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[because]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;did not recognize&rdquo;) which is understood as causal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> did not recognize this one, and the voices of the prophets that are read on every Sabbath, fulfilled <i>[them]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> <i>[by]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[by]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;condemning&rdquo;) which is understood as means."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> condemning <i>[him]</i>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:28">28</span></font></b> And <i>[although they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[although]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;found&rdquo;) which is understood as concessive."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> found no charge <i>[worthy]</i> of death, they asked Pilate <i>[that]</i> he be executed. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:29">29</span></font></b> And when they had carried out all the things that were written about him, they took <i>[him]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> down from the tree <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;took ... down&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> placed <i>[him]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> in a tomb. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:30">30</span></font></b> But God raised him from the dead, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:31">31</span></font></b> who appeared for many days to those who had come up with him from Galilee to Jerusalem--who are now his witnesses to the people. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:32">32</span></font></b> And we proclaim the good news to you: that the promise that was made to the fathers, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:33">33</span></font></b> this <i>[promise]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="It is necessary to repeat the word &ldquo;<i>[promise]</i>&rdquo; from the previous verse for clarity here."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> God has fulfilled to our children<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Some manuscripts have &ldquo;to us their children.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> <i>[by]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[by]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;raising&rdquo;) which is understood as means."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> raising Jesus, as it is also written in the second psalm, &apos;You are my Son; today I have fathered you.&apos;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A quotation from Ps 2:7."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="13:34">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:34">34</span></font></b> But that he has raised him from the dead, no more going to return to decay, he has spoken in this way: &apos;I will give you the reliable divine decrees of David.&apos;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A quotation from Isa 55:3."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:35">35</span></font></b> Therefore he also says in another <i>[psalm]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The word &ldquo;<i>[psalm]</i>&rdquo; is not in the Greek text but is implied."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> &apos;You will not permit your Holy One to experience decay.&apos;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A quotation from Ps 16:10."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="13:36">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:36">36</span></font></b> For David, <i>[after]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;serving&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> serving the purpose of God in his own generation, fell asleep and <u>was buried with</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;was gathered to.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> his fathers, and experienced decay. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:37">37</span></font></b> But he whom God raised up did not experience decay. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="13:38">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:38">38</span></font></b> &ldquo;Therefore let it be known to you, men <i>[and]</i> brothers, that through this one forgiveness of sins is proclaimed to you, and from all <i>[the things]</i> from which you were not able to be justified by the law of Moses, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:39">39</span></font></b> by this one everyone who believes is justified! <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:40">40</span></font></b> Watch out, therefore, lest what is stated by the prophets come upon <i>[you]</i>:<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="13:41">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:41">41</span></font></b> &apos;Look, you scoffers, and be astonished and perish! For I am doing a work in your days, a work that you would never believe <i>[even]</i> if someone were to tell <i>[it]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to you.&apos;&rdquo;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A quotation from Hab 1:5."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="13:42">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:42">42</span></font></b> And <i>[as]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[as]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;were going out&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> they were going out, they began urging<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The imperfect tense has been translated as ingressive here (&ldquo;began urging&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> <i>[that]</i> these things be spoken about to them on the next Sabbath. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:43">43</span></font></b> And <i>[after]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;had broken up&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the synagogue had broken up, many of the Jews and the devout<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;God-fearing.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> proselytes followed Paul and Barnabas, who were speaking to them <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;were speaking to&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> were persuading them to continue in the grace of God. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:44">44</span></font></b> And on the coming Sabbath, nearly the whole city came together to hear the word of the Lord. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:45">45</span></font></b> But <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;saw&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the Jews saw the crowds, they were filled with jealousy, and began contradicting what was being said by Paul <i>[by]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[by]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;reviling&rdquo;) which is understood as means."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> reviling <i>[him]</i>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:46">46</span></font></b> Both Paul and Barnabas spoke boldly <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;spoke boldly&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said, &ldquo;It was necessary <i>[that]</i> the word of God be spoken first to you, since you reject it and do not consider yourselves worthy of eternal life! Behold, we are turning to the Gentiles! <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:47">47</span></font></b> For so the Lord has commanded us: &apos;I have appointed you <u>to be</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;for.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> a light for the Gentiles, <u>that you would bring</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;<i>[that]</i> you would bring.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> salvation to the end of the earth.&apos;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="An allusion to Isa 42:6; 49:6."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="13:48">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:48">48</span></font></b> And <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;heard&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the Gentiles heard <i>[this]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> they began to rejoice<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The imperfect tense has been translated as ingressive here (&ldquo;began to rejoice&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and to glorify the word of the Lord. And all those who were designated for eternal life believed. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:49">49</span></font></b> So the word of the Lord was carried through the whole region. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:50">50</span></font></b> But the Jews incited the devout women of high social standing and the most prominent men of the city, and stirred up persecution against Paul and Barnabas and threw them out of their district. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:51">51</span></font></b> So <i>[after]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;shaking off&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> shaking off the dust from <i>[their]</i> feet against them, they went to Iconium. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:52">52</span></font></b> And the disciples were filled with joy and with the Holy Spirit. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="14:1">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="14:1">14:1</span></font></b> Now it happened that in Iconium they entered <u>together</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;according to the same.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> into the synagogue of the Jews and spoke in such a way that a large number of both Jews and Greeks believed. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="14:2">2</span></font></b> But the Jews who were disobedient stirred up and <u>poisoned the minds</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;embittered the souls.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> of the Gentiles against the brothers. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="14:3">3</span></font></b> So they stayed <i>[there]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> for a considerable time, speaking boldly for the Lord, who testified to the message of his grace, granting signs and wonders to be performed through their hands. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="14:4">4</span></font></b> But the population of the city was divided, and <u>some</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;those on the one hand.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> were with the Jews <u>and some</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;those on the other hand.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> with the apostles. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="14:5">5</span></font></b> So when an inclination took place <i>[on the part]</i> of both the Gentiles and the Jews, together with their rulers, to mistreat <i>[them]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and to stone them, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="14:6">6</span></font></b> they became aware of <i>[it]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;became aware of&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> fled to the Lycaonian cities--Lystra and Derbe and the surrounding region. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="14:7">7</span></font></b> And there they were continuing to proclaim the good news. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="14:8">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="14:8">8</span></font></b> And in Lystra a certain man was sitting powerless in his feet, lame from <u>birth</u>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;his mother&apos;s womb.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> who had never walked. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="14:9">9</span></font></b> This man listened <i>[while]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[while]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;was speaking&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Paul was speaking. <u>Paul</u>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;who.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> looking intently at him and seeing that he had faith to be healed, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="14:10">10</span></font></b> said with a loud voice, &ldquo;Stand upright on your feet!&rdquo; And he leaped up and began walking.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The imperfect tense has been translated as ingressive here (&ldquo;began walking&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="14:11">11</span></font></b> And <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;saw&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the crowds saw what Paul had done, they raised their voices in the Lycaonian language, saying, &ldquo;The gods have become like men <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;have become like&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> have come down to us!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="14:12">12</span></font></b> And they began calling<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The imperfect tense has been translated as ingressive here (&ldquo;began calling&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Barnabas Zeus and Paul Hermes, because he was the <u>principal speaker</u>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;leader of the message.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="14:13">13</span></font></b> And the priest of the <i>[temple]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The word &ldquo;<i>[temple]</i>&rdquo; is not in the Greek text but is implied."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> of Zeus that was just outside the city brought bulls and garlands to the gates <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;brought&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> was wanting to offer sacrifice, along with the crowds. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="14:14">14</span></font></b> But <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;heard about&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the apostles Barnabas and Paul heard about <i>[it]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> they tore their clothing <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;tore&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> rushed out into the crowd, shouting <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="14:15">15</span></font></b> and saying, &ldquo;Men, why are you doing these <i>[things]</i>? We also are men with the same nature as you, proclaiming the good news <i>[that]</i> you should turn from these worthless things to the living God, who made the heaven and the earth and the sea and all the things <i>[that are]</i> in them-- <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="14:16">16</span></font></b> who in generations that are past permitted all the nations<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;Gentiles&rdquo;; the same Greek word can be translated &ldquo;nations&rdquo; or &ldquo;Gentiles&rdquo; depending on the context."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to go their <i>[own]</i> ways. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="14:17">17</span></font></b> And yet he did not leave himself without witness <i>[by]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[by]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;doing good&rdquo;) which is understood as means."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> doing good, giving you rain from heaven and fruitful seasons, satisfying <i>[you]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> with food and your hearts with gladness.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="14:18">18</span></font></b> And <i>[although]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[although]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;said&rdquo;) which is understood as concessive."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> they said these <i>[things]</i>, <i>[only]</i> with difficulty did they dissuade the crowds from offering sacrifice to them. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="14:19">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="14:19">19</span></font></b> But Jews arrived from Antioch and Iconium, and <i>[when they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;had won over&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> had won over the crowds and stoned Paul, they dragged <i>[him]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> outside the city, thinking he was dead. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="14:20">20</span></font></b> But <i>[after]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;surrounded&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the disciples surrounded him, he got up <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;got up&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> went into the city. And on the next day he departed with Barnabas for Derbe. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="14:21">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="14:21">21</span></font></b> And <i>[after they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;had proclaimed the good news&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> had proclaimed the good news in that city and made many disciples, they returned to Lystra and to Iconium and to Antioch, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="14:22">22</span></font></b> strengthening the souls of the disciples, encouraging <i>[them]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to continue in the faith and <i>[saying]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The word &ldquo;<i>[saying]</i>&rdquo; is not in the Greek text but is implied."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> &ldquo;Through many persecutions<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;afflictions.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> it is necessary <i>[for]</i> us to enter into the kingdom of God.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="14:23">23</span></font></b> And <i>[when they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;had appointed&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> had appointed elders for them in every church, <i>[after]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;praying&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> praying with fasting, they entrusted them to the Lord, in whom they had believed. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="14:24">24</span></font></b> And they passed through Pisidia <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;passed through&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> came to Pamphylia. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="14:25">25</span></font></b> And <i>[after]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;proclaimed&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> they proclaimed the message in Perga, they went down to Attalia, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="14:26">26</span></font></b> and from there they sailed away to Antioch where they had been commended to the grace of God for the work that they had completed. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="14:27">27</span></font></b> And <i>[when they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;arrived&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> arrived and called the church together, they reported all that God had done with them, and that he had opened a door of faith for the Gentiles.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;nations&rdquo;; the same Greek word can be translated &ldquo;nations&rdquo; or &ldquo;Gentiles&rdquo; depending on the context."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="14:28">28</span></font></b> And they stayed no little time with the disciples. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="15:1">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:1">15:1</span></font></b> And some men came down from Judea <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;came down&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> began teaching<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The imperfect tense has been translated as ingressive here (&ldquo;began teaching&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the brothers, &ldquo;Unless you are circumcised according to the custom <i>[prescribed]</i> by Moses, you cannot be saved.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:2">2</span></font></b> And <i>[after]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;was&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> there was no little strife and debate by Paul and Barnabas against them, they appointed Paul and Barnabas and some others from among them to go up to the apostles and elders in Jerusalem concerning this issue. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:3">3</span></font></b> So they were sent on their way by the church, <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;were sent on their way&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> passed through both Phoenicia and Samaria, telling in detail the conversion of the Gentiles and bringing great joy to all the brothers. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:4">4</span></font></b> And <i>[when they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;arrived&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> arrived in Jerusalem, they were received by the church and the apostles and the elders, and reported all that God had done with them. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:5">5</span></font></b> But some of those who had believed from the party of the Pharisees stood up, saying, &ldquo;It is necessary to circumcise them and to command <i>[them]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to observe the law of Moses!&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="15:6">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:6">6</span></font></b> Both the apostles and the elders assembled to deliberate concerning this matter. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:7">7</span></font></b> And <i>[after]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;was&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> there was much debate, Peter stood up <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;stood up&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said to them, &ldquo;Men <i>[and]</i> brothers, you know that in the early days<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;from ancient days.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> God chose among you through my mouth <i>[that]</i> the Gentiles should hear the message of the gospel and believe. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:8">8</span></font></b> And God, who knows the heart, testified to them <i>[by]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[by]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;giving&rdquo;) which is understood as means."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> giving <i>[them]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the Holy Spirit, just as he also <i>[did]</i> to us. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:9">9</span></font></b> And he made no distinction between us and them, cleansing their hearts by faith. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:10">10</span></font></b> So now why are you putting God to the test <i>[by]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[by]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the infinitive (&ldquo;placing&rdquo;) which is understood as means."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> placing on the neck of the disciples a yoke that neither our fathers nor we have been able to bear? <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:11">11</span></font></b> But we believe <i>[we]</i> will be saved through the grace of the Lord Jesus in <u>the same</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;which.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> way those also <i>[are]</i>.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:12">12</span></font></b> And the whole group became silent and listened to Barnabas and Paul describing all the signs and wonders God had done among the Gentiles through them. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:13">13</span></font></b> And after they had stopped speaking, James answered, saying, &ldquo;Men <i>[and]</i> brothers, listen to me! <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:14">14</span></font></b> Simeon has described how God first concerned himself to take from among the Gentiles a people for his name. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:15">15</span></font></b> And with this the words of the prophets agree, just as it is written: </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="15:16">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:16">16</span></font></b> &apos;After these <i>[things]</i> I will return and build up again the tent of David that has fallen, and the <i>[parts]</i> of it that had been torn down I will build up again and will restore it, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:17">17</span></font></b> so that the rest of humanity may seek the Lord, even all the Gentiles<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The same Greek word can be translated &ldquo;nations&rdquo; or &ldquo;Gentiles&rdquo; depending on the context."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> <u>who are called by my name</u>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;on whom my name has been called on them.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> says the Lord,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A quotation from Amos 9:11-12."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> who makes these <i>[things]</i> <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:18">18</span></font></b> known from of old.&apos;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The last phrase of v. 17 and all of v. 18 is an allusion to Isa 45:21."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="15:19">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:19">19</span></font></b> Therefore I conclude we should not cause difficulty for those from among the Gentiles who turn to God, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:20">20</span></font></b> but we should write a letter to them to abstain from the pollution of idols and from sexual immorality and from what has been strangled and from blood. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:21">21</span></font></b> For Moses has those who proclaim him in every city from ancient generations, <i>[because he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[because]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;is read aloud&rdquo;) which is understood as causal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> is read aloud in the synagogues on every Sabbath.&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="15:22">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:22">22</span></font></b> Then it seemed best to the apostles and the elders, together with the whole church, to send men chosen from among them to Antioch with Paul and Barnabas--Judas who was called Barsabbas and Silas, men <i>[who were]</i> leaders among the brothers-- <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:23">23</span></font></b> writing <i>[this letter]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> <u>to be delivered by them</u>:<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;by their hand.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> The apostles and the elders, brothers. To the brothers <i>[who are]</i> from among the Gentiles in Antioch and Syria and Cilicia.Greetings! <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:24">24</span></font></b> Because we have heard that some have gone out from among us--to whom we gave no orders--<i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;have gone out&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> have thrown you into confusion by words upsetting your <u>minds</u>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;souls.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:25">25</span></font></b> it seemed best to us, <u>having reached a unanimous decision</u>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;having become of one mind.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied in keeping with English style."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> having chosen men, to send <i>[them]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to you together with our dear friends Barnabas and Paul, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:26">26</span></font></b> men who have risked their lives on behalf of the name of our Lord Jesus Christ. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:27">27</span></font></b> Therefore we have sent Judas and Silas, and they will report the same <i>[things]</i> by word of mouth. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:28">28</span></font></b> For it seemed best to the Holy Spirit and to us to place on you no greater burden except these necessary things: <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:29">29</span></font></b> <i>[that you]</i> abstain from food sacrificed to idols, and from blood, and from what has been strangled, and from sexual immorality. <i>[If you]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[if]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;keep&rdquo;) which is understood as conditional."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> keep yourselves from <u>these things</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;which things.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> you will do well. Farewell.</p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="15:30">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:30">30</span></font></b> So <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;were sent off&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> they were sent off, they came down to Antioch, and <i>[after]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;calling together&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> calling together the community, they delivered the letter. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:31">31</span></font></b> And <i>[when they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;read ... aloud&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> read <i>[it]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> aloud, they rejoiced at the encouragement. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:32">32</span></font></b> Both Judas and Silas, who were also prophets themselves, encouraged and strengthened the brothers by a long message. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:33">33</span></font></b> And <i>[after]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;spending&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> spending <i>[some]</i> time, they were sent away in peace from the brothers to those who had sent them.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A few later manuscripts add v. 34, &ldquo;But Silas decided to stay there.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:35">35</span></font></b> But Paul and Barnabas remained in Antioch teaching and proclaiming the word of the Lord with many others also. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="15:36">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:36">36</span></font></b> And after some days, Paul said to Barnabas, &ldquo;Come then,<i>[let us]</i> return <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;return&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> visit the brothers in every town in which we proclaimed the word of the Lord, <i>[to see]</i> how they are <i>[doing]</i>.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:37">37</span></font></b> Now Barnabas wanted to take John who was called Mark along also, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:38">38</span></font></b> but Paul held the opinion they should not take this one along, who departed from them in Pamphylia and did not accompany them in the work. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:39">39</span></font></b> And a sharp disagreement took place, so that they separated from one another. And Barnabas took along Mark <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;took along&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> sailed away to Cyprus, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:40">40</span></font></b> but Paul chose Silas <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;chose&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> departed, <i>[after]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;being commended&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> being commended to the grace of the Lord by the brothers. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:41">41</span></font></b> And he traveled through Syria and Cilicia, strengthening the churches. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="16:1">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="16:1">16:1</span></font></b> And he came also to Derbe and to Lystra. And behold, a certain disciple was there <u>named</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;by name.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Timothy, the son of a believing Jewish woman but of a Greek father, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="16:2">2</span></font></b> who was well spoken of by the brothers in Lystra and Iconium. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="16:3">3</span></font></b> Paul wanted this one to go with him, and he took <i>[him]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;took&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> circumcised him because of the Jews who were in those places, for <i>[they]</i> all knew that his father was Greek. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="16:4">4</span></font></b> And as they went through the towns, they passed on to them to observe the rules that had been decided by the apostles and elders <i>[who were]</i> in Jerusalem. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="16:5">5</span></font></b> So the churches were being strengthened in the faith and were growing in number every day. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="16:6">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="16:6">6</span></font></b> And they traveled through the Phrygian and Galatian region, having been prevented by the Holy Spirit from speaking the message in Asia.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A reference to the Roman province of Asia (modern Asia Minor)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="16:7">7</span></font></b> And <i>[when they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;came&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> came to Mysia, they attempted to go into Bithynia, and the Spirit of Jesus did not permit them. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="16:8">8</span></font></b> So going through Mysia, they went down to Troas. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="16:9">9</span></font></b> And a vision appeared to Paul during the night: a certain Macedonian man was standing there and imploring him and saying, &ldquo;Come over to Macedonia <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;come over&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> help us!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="16:10">10</span></font></b> And when he had seen the vision, we wanted at once to go away to Macedonia, concluding that God had called us to proclaim the good news to them. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="16:11">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="16:11">11</span></font></b> So putting out to sea from Troas, we sailed a straight course to Samothrace, and on the following <i>[day]</i> to Neapolis, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="16:12">12</span></font></b> and from there to Philippi, which is a leading city <i>[of that]</i> district of Macedonia, a <i>[Roman]</i> colony. And we were staying in this city for some days. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="16:13">13</span></font></b> And on the day of the Sabbath, we went outside the <i>[city]</i> gate beside the river, where we thought there was a place of prayer, and we sat down <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;sat down&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> spoke to the women assembled <i>[there]</i>. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="16:14">14</span></font></b> And a certain woman <u>named</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;by name.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Lydia from the city of Thyatira, a merchant dealing in purple cloth who showed reverence for God, was listening. The Lord opened <u>her</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;whose.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> heart to pay attention to what was being said by Paul. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="16:15">15</span></font></b> And after she was baptized, and her household, she urged <i>[us]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> saying, &ldquo;If you consider me to be a believer in the Lord, come to my house <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;come&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> stay.&rdquo; And she prevailed upon us. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="16:16">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="16:16">16</span></font></b> And it happened that <i>[as]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[as]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;were going&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> we were going to the place of prayer, a certain female slave who had a spirit of divination<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;a spirit of Python&rdquo;; Python was the name of the serpent or dragon that guarded the Delphic oracle at the foot of Mt. Parnassus and the word eventually came to be used for a spirit of divination."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> met us, who was bringing a large profit to her owners <i>[by]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[by]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the infinitive (&ldquo;fortune-telling&rdquo;) which is understood as means."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> fortune-telling. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="16:17">17</span></font></b> She followed Paul and us <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;followed&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> was crying out, saying, &ldquo;These men are slaves of the Most High God, who are proclaiming to you the way of salvation!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="16:18">18</span></font></b> And she was doing this for many days. But Paul, becoming greatly annoyed and turning around, said to the spirit, &ldquo;I command you in the name of Jesus Christ to come out of her!&rdquo; And it came out <u>immediately</u>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;<i>[that]</i> same hour.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="16:19">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="16:19">19</span></font></b> But <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;saw&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> her owners saw that their hope of profit was gone, they seized Paul and Silas <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;seized&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> dragged <i>[them]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> into the marketplace before the rulers. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="16:20">20</span></font></b> And <i>[when they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;had brought&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> had brought them to the chief magistrates, they said, &ldquo;These men are throwing our city into confusion, being Jews, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="16:21">21</span></font></b> and are proclaiming customs that are not permitted for us to accept or to practice, <i>[because we]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[because]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;are&rdquo;) which is understood as causal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> are Romans!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="16:22">22</span></font></b> And the crowd joined in attacking them, and the chief magistrates tore off their clothing <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;tore off&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> gave orders to beat <i>[them]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> with rods. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="16:23">23</span></font></b> And <i>[after they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;had inflicted&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> had inflicted many blows on them, they threw <i>[them]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> into prison, giving orders to the jailer to guard them securely. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="16:24">24</span></font></b> Having received such an order, <u>he</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;who.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> put them in the inner prison and fastened their feet in the stocks.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or possibly &ldquo;to the <i>[block]</i> of wood,&rdquo; referring to a log to which the prisoners were chained or tied."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="16:25">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="16:25">25</span></font></b> Now about midnight, Paul and Silas were praying <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;were praying&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> singing hymns to God, and the prisoners were listening to them. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="16:26">26</span></font></b> And suddenly there was a great earthquake, so that the foundations of the prison were shaken. And immediately all the doors were opened and all the bonds<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;chains.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> were unfastened. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="16:27">27</span></font></b> And <i>[after]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;was&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the jailer was awake and saw the doors of the prison open, he drew <i>[his]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> sword <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;drew&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> was about to kill himself, <i>[because he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[because]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;thought&rdquo;) which is understood as causal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> thought the prisoners had escaped. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="16:28">28</span></font></b> But Paul called out with a loud voice, saying, &ldquo;Do no harm to yourself, for we are all here!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="16:29">29</span></font></b> And demanding lights, he rushed in and, <u>beginning to tremble</u>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;became trembling.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> fell down at the feet of Paul and Silas. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="16:30">30</span></font></b> And he brought them outside <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;brought&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said, &ldquo;Sirs, what must I do so that I can be saved?&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="16:31">31</span></font></b> And they said, &ldquo;Believe in the Lord Jesus and you will be saved, you and your household!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="16:32">32</span></font></b> And they spoke the message of the Lord to him, together with all those in his house. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="16:33">33</span></font></b> And he took them at that <i>[very]</i> hour of the night <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;took&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> washed <i>[their]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> wounds, and he himself was baptized at once, and all those of his <i>[household]</i>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The word &ldquo;<i>[household]</i>&rdquo; is not in the Greek text, but is supplied from the previous verse."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="16:34">34</span></font></b> And he brought them up into <i>[his]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> house <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;brought ... up&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> set a meal before <i>[them]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and rejoiced greatly that he had believed in God with his whole household. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="16:35">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="16:35">35</span></font></b> And <i>[when it]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;was&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> was day, the chief magistrates sent the police officers, saying, &ldquo;Release those men.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="16:36">36</span></font></b> And the jailer reported these words to Paul: &ldquo;The chief magistrates have sent <i>[an order]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> that you should be released. So come out now <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;come out&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> go in peace!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="16:37">37</span></font></b> But Paul said to them, &ldquo;They beat us in public without due process--men who are Roman citizens--<i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;beat&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> threw <i>[us]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> into prison, and now they are wanting to release us secretly? Certainly not! Rather let them come themselves <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;come&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> bring us out!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="16:38">38</span></font></b> So the police officers reported these words to the chief magistrates, and they were afraid <i>[when they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;heard&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> heard that they were Roman citizens. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="16:39">39</span></font></b> And they came <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;came&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> apologized to<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;reassured&rdquo;; or &ldquo;conciliated.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> them, and <i>[after they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;brought ... out&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> brought <i>[them]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> out they asked <i>[them]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to depart from the city. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="16:40">40</span></font></b> And <i>[when they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;came out&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> came out of the prison, they went to Lydia and <i>[when they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;saw&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> saw <i>[them]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> they encouraged the brothers and departed. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="17:1">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="17:1">17:1</span></font></b> Now <i>[after they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;traveled through&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> traveled through Amphipolis and Apollonia, they came to Thessalonica, where there was a synagogue of the Jews. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="17:2">2</span></font></b> <u>And as was his custom</u>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;and in accordance with what he was accustomed to.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Paul went in to them and on three Sabbath <i>[days]</i> he discussed with them from the scriptures, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="17:3">3</span></font></b> explaining and demonstrating that it was necessary <i>[for]</i> the Christ<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;Messiah.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to suffer and to rise from the dead, and <i>[saying]</i>, &ldquo;This Jesus whom I am proclaiming to you is the Christ.&rdquo;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;Messiah.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="17:4">4</span></font></b> And some of them were persuaded and joined Paul and Silas, and <i>[also]</i> a large number of God-fearing Greeks and not a few of the prominent women. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="17:5">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="17:5">5</span></font></b> But the Jews were filled with jealousy and, taking along some worthless men from the rabble in the marketplace and forming a mob, threw the city into an uproar. And attacking Jason&apos;s house, they were looking for them to bring <i>[them]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> out to the popular assembly. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="17:6">6</span></font></b> And <i>[when they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;find&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> did not find them, they dragged Jason and some brothers before the city officials, shouting, &ldquo;These <i>[people]</i> who have stirred up trouble <i>[throughout]</i> the world<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;empire.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> have come here also, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="17:7">7</span></font></b> whom Jason has entertained as guests! And these <i>[people]</i> <i>[are]</i> all acting contrary to the decrees of Caesar, saying there is another king, Jesus!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="17:8">8</span></font></b> And they threw the crowd into confusion, and the city officials who heard these <i>[things]</i>. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="17:9">9</span></font></b> And <i>[after]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;taking&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> taking money as security from Jason and the rest, they released them. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="17:10">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="17:10">10</span></font></b> Now the brothers sent away both Paul and Silas at once, during the night, to Berea. <u>They</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;who&rdquo; (referring to Paul and Silas)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> went into the synagogue of the Jews <i>[when they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;arrived&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> arrived. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="17:11">11</span></font></b> Now these were more open-minded than those in Thessalonica. <u>They</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;who.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> accepted the message with all eagerness, examining the scriptures every day <i>[to see]</i> if these <i>[things]</i> were so. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="17:12">12</span></font></b> Therefore many of them believed, and not a few of the prominent Greek women and men. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="17:13">13</span></font></b> But when the Jews from Thessalonica found out that the message of God had been proclaimed by Paul in Berea also, they came there too, inciting and stirring up the crowds. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="17:14">14</span></font></b> So then the brothers sent Paul away at once to go to the sea, and both Silas and Timothy remained there. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="17:15">15</span></font></b> And those who conducted Paul brought <i>[him]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> as far as Athens, and <i>[after]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;receiving&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> receiving an order for Silas and Timothy that they should come to him as soon as possible, they went away. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="17:16">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="17:16">16</span></font></b> Now while Paul was waiting for them in Athens, his spirit was provoked within him <i>[when he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;observed&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> observed the city was full of idols. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="17:17">17</span></font></b> So he was discussing in the synagogue with the Jews and the God-fearing <i>[Gentiles]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the word &ldquo;<i>[Gentiles]</i>&rdquo; is not in the Greek text but is implied."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and in the marketplace every day with those who happened to be there. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="17:18">18</span></font></b> And even some of the Epicurean and Stoic philosophers were conversing with him, and some were saying, &ldquo;What does this babbler want to say?&rdquo; But <i>[others said]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The words &ldquo;<i>[others said]</i>&rdquo; are not in the Greek text but are implied."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> &ldquo;He appears to be a proclaimer of foreign deities,&rdquo; because he was proclaiming the good news <i>[about]</i> Jesus and the resurrection. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="17:19">19</span></font></b> And they took hold of him <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;took hold of&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> brought <i>[him]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to the Areopagus, saying, &ldquo;May we learn what <i>[is]</i> this new teaching being proclaimed by you? <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="17:20">20</span></font></b> For you are bringing some astonishing things to our ears. Therefore we want to know what <u>these things mean</u>.&rdquo;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;these <i>[things]</i> want to be.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="17:21">21</span></font></b> (Now all the Athenians and the foreigners who stayed there used to spend <i>[their]</i> time in nothing else than telling something or listening to something new.) </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="17:22">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="17:22">22</span></font></b> So Paul stood there in the middle of the Areopagus <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;stood there&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said, &ldquo;Men of Athens, I see you <i>[are]</i> very religious <u>in every respect</u>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;with respect to all <i>[things]</i>.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="17:23">23</span></font></b> For <i>[as I]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[as]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;was passing through&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> was passing through and observing carefully your objects of worship, I even found an altar on which was inscribed, &apos;To an unknown God.&apos; Therefore what you worship without knowing <i>[it]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> this I proclaim to you-- <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="17:24">24</span></font></b> the God who made the world and all the things in it. This one, being Lord of heaven and earth, does not live in temples made by human hands, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="17:25">25</span></font></b> nor is he served by human hands <i>[as if he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[as]</i> if&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the conditional adverbial participle (&ldquo;needed&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> needed anything, <i>[because]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[because]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;gives&rdquo;) which is understood as causal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> he himself gives to everyone life and breath and everything. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="17:26">26</span></font></b> And he made from one <i>[man]</i> every nation of humanity to live on all the face of the earth, determining <i>[their]</i> fixed times and the fixed boundaries of their habitation, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="17:27">27</span></font></b> to search for God, if perhaps indeed they might feel around for him and find <i>[him]</i>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> And indeed he is not far away from each one of us, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="17:28">28</span></font></b> for in him we live and move and exist,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Some interpreters hold that the phrase &ldquo;in him we live and move and exist&rdquo; is a quotation from Epimenides of Crete, but more likely it is a traditional Greek formula."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> as even some of <u>your own</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;with respect to you.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> poets have said: &apos;For we also are <u>his</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;of <i>[him]</i>.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> offspring.&apos;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A quotation from Aratus, Phaenomena 5."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="17:29">29</span></font></b> Therefore, <i>[because we]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[because]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;are&rdquo;) which is understood as causal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> are offspring of God, we ought not to think the divine being is like gold or silver or stone, an image formed by human skill and thought. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="17:30">30</span></font></b> Therefore <i>[although]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[although]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;has overlooked&rdquo;) which is understood as concessive."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> God has overlooked the times of ignorance, he now commands all people everywhere to repent, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="17:31">31</span></font></b> because he has set a day on which he is going to judge the world in righteousness by the man who he has appointed, having provided proof to everyone <i>[by]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[by]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;raising&rdquo;) which is understood as means."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> raising him from the dead.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="17:32">32</span></font></b> Now <i>[when they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;heard about&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> heard about the resurrection of the dead, <i>[some]</i> scoffed, but <i>[others]</i> said, &ldquo;We will hear you about this again also.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="17:33">33</span></font></b> So Paul went out from the midst of them. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="17:34">34</span></font></b> But some people<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the Greek term &ldquo;men&rdquo; is used as a generic for &ldquo;people&rdquo;; note the presence of of a woman (Damaris) in the group."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> joined him <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;joined&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> believed, among whom also <i>[were]</i> Dionysius the Areopagite and a woman <u>named</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;by name.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Damaris and others with them. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="18:1">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="18:1">18:1</span></font></b> After these <i>[things]</i> he departed from Athens <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;departed&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> went to Corinth. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="18:2">2</span></font></b> And he found a certain Jew <u>named</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;by name.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Aquila, <u>a native</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;by nationality.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> of Pontus who had arrived recently from Italy <u>along with</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;and.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Priscilla his wife, because Claudius had ordered all the Jews to depart from Rome, <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;found&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> he went to them. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="18:3">3</span></font></b> And because <i>[he]</i> was practicing the same trade, he stayed with them and worked, for they were tentmakers by trade. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="18:4">4</span></font></b> And he argued in the synagogue every Sabbath, attempting to persuade<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the imperfect verb has been translated as conative (&ldquo;attempting to persuade&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> both Jews and Greeks. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="18:5">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="18:5">5</span></font></b> Now when both Silas and Timothy came down from Macedonia, Paul began to be occupied with<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The imperfect tense has been translated as ingressive here (&ldquo;began to be occupied with&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the message, solemnly testifying to the Jews <i>[that]</i> the Christ<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;Messiah.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> was Jesus. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="18:6">6</span></font></b> And <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;resisted&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> they resisted and reviled <i>[him]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> he shook out <i>[his]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> clothes <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;shook out&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said to them, &ldquo;Your blood <i>[be]</i> on your <i>[own]</i> heads! I <i>[am]</i> guiltless! From now on I will go to the Gentiles!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="18:7">7</span></font></b> And leaving there, he entered into the house of someone <u>named</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;by name.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Titius Justus, a worshiper<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;a God-fearer.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> of God whose house was next door to the synagogue. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="18:8">8</span></font></b> And Crispus, the ruler of the synagogue, believed in the Lord together with his whole household. And many of the Corinthians, <i>[when they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;heard about&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> heard about <i>[it]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> believed and were baptized. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="18:9">9</span></font></b> And the Lord said to Paul by a vision in the night, &ldquo;Do not be afraid, but speak and do not keep silent, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="18:10">10</span></font></b> because I am with you and no one will attack you to harm you, because many people are mine in this city.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="18:11">11</span></font></b> So he stayed a year and six months, teaching the word of God among them. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="18:12">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="18:12">12</span></font></b> Now <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;was&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Gallio was proconsul of Achaia, the Jews rose up with one purpose against Paul and brought him before the judgment seat, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="18:13">13</span></font></b> saying, &ldquo;This man is persuading people to worship God contrary to the law!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="18:14">14</span></font></b> But <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;was about&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Paul was about to open <i>[his]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> mouth, Gallio said to the Jews, &ldquo;If it was some crime or wicked villainy, O Jews, <u>I would have been justified in accepting</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;with respect to a motive I would have accepted.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> your complaint. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="18:15">15</span></font></b> But if it is questions concerning a word and names and <u>your own law</u>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the according to you law.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> see to <i>[it]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> yourselves! I do not wish to be a judge of these <i>[things]</i>.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="18:16">16</span></font></b> And he drove them away from the judgment seat. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="18:17">17</span></font></b> So they all seized Sosthenes, the ruler of the synagogue, <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;seized&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> began beating<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The imperfect tense has been translated as ingressive here (&ldquo;began beating&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> <i>[him]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> in front of the judgment seat. And none of these <i>[things]</i> was a concern to Gallio. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="18:18">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="18:18">18</span></font></b> So Paul, <i>[after]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;remaining&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> remaining many days longer, said farewell to the brothers <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;said farewell&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> sailed away to Syria, and with him Priscilla and Aquila. He shaved <i>[his]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> head at Cenchrea, because he had <i>[taken]</i> a vow. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="18:19">19</span></font></b> So they arrived at Ephesus, and those he left behind there, but he himself entered into the synagogue <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;entered&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> discussed with the Jews. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="18:20">20</span></font></b> And <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;asked&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> they asked <i>[him]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to stay for a longer time, he did not give his consent, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="18:21">21</span></font></b> but saying farewell and telling <i>[them]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> &ldquo;I will return to you again <i>[if]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;if&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the conditional adverbial participle (&ldquo;wills&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> God wills,&rdquo; he set sail from Ephesus. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="18:22">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="18:22">22</span></font></b> And <i>[when he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;arrived&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> arrived at Caesarea, he went up and greeted the church, <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the two previous participles (&ldquo;went up&rdquo; and &ldquo;greeted&rdquo;) have been translated as finite verbs."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> went down to Antioch. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="18:23">23</span></font></b> And <i>[after]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;spending&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> spending some time <i>[there]</i>, he departed, traveling through one <i>[place]</i> after another <i>[in]</i> the Galatian region and Phrygia, strengthening all the disciples. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="18:24">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="18:24">24</span></font></b> Now a certain Jew <u>named</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;by name.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Apollos, <u>a native</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;by nationality.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Alexandrian, arrived in Ephesus--an eloquent man who was well-versed in the scriptures. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="18:25">25</span></font></b> This man had been instructed <i>[in]</i> the way of the Lord, and being enthusiastic in spirit, he was speaking and teaching accurately the <i>[things]</i> about Jesus, <i>[although he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[although]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;knew&rdquo;) which is understood as concessive."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> knew only the baptism of John. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="18:26">26</span></font></b> And he began to speak boldly in the synagogue, but <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;heard&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Priscilla and Aquila heard him, they took him aside and explained the way of God to him more accurately. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="18:27">27</span></font></b> And <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;wanted&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> he wanted to cross over to Achaia, the brothers encouraged <i>[him]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;encouraged&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> wrote to the disciples to welcome him. <i>[When he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;arrived&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> arrived, <u>he</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;who.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> assisted greatly those who had believed through grace. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="18:28">28</span></font></b> For he was vigorously refuting the Jews in public, demonstrating through the scriptures <i>[that]</i> the Christ<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;Messiah.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> was Jesus. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="19:1">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="19:1">19:1</span></font></b> And it happened that <i>[while]</i> Apollos was in Corinth, Paul traveled through the inland regions <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;traveled through&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> came<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Some manuscripts have &ldquo;<i>[and]</i> came down.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to Ephesus and found some disciples. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="19:2">2</span></font></b> And he said to them, &ldquo;Did you receive the Holy Spirit <i>[when you]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;believed&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> believed?&rdquo; And they <i>[said]</i> to him, &ldquo;But we have not even heard that there is a Holy Spirit!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="19:3">3</span></font></b> And he said, &ldquo;Into what then were you baptized?&rdquo; And they said, &ldquo;Into the baptism of John.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="19:4">4</span></font></b> And Paul said, &ldquo;John baptized <i>[with]</i> a baptism of repentance, telling the people that they should believe in the one who was to come after him--that is, in Jesus.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="19:5">5</span></font></b> And <i>[when they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;heard&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> heard <i>[this]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> they were baptized in the name of the Lord Jesus. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="19:6">6</span></font></b> And <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;laid&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Paul laid hands<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Some manuscripts have &ldquo;placed his hands.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> on them, the Holy Spirit came upon them and they began to speak<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The imperfect tense has been translated as ingressive here (&ldquo;began to speak&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> in tongues and to prophesy. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="19:7">7</span></font></b> (Now the total <i>[number]</i> <i>[of]</i> men was about twelve.) </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="19:8">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="19:8">8</span></font></b> So he entered into the synagogue <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;entered&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> was speaking boldly for three months, discussing and attempting to convince<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The present tense participle has been translated as a conative present (&ldquo;attempting to convince&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> <i>[them]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> concerning<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Some manuscripts have &ldquo;<i>[of]</i> the things concerning.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the kingdom of God. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="19:9">9</span></font></b> But when some became hardened and were disobedient, reviling the Way before the congregation, he departed from them <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;departed&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> took away the disciples, leading discussions every day in the lecture hall of Tyrannus. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="19:10">10</span></font></b> And this took place for two years, so that all who lived in Asia<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A reference to the Roman province of Asia (modern Asia Minor)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> heard the word of the Lord, both Jews and Greeks. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="19:11">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="19:11">11</span></font></b> And God was performing <u>extraordinary</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;not the ordinary.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> miracles by the hands of Paul, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="19:12">12</span></font></b> so that even handkerchiefs or work aprons <u>that had touched his skin</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;from his skin.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> were carried away to those who were sick, and <i>[their]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> diseases left them and the evil spirits came out <i>[of them]</i>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The words &ldquo;<i>[of them]</i>&rdquo; are not in the Greek text but are implied."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="19:13">13</span></font></b> But some itinerant Jewish exorcists also attempted to pronounce the name of the Lord Jesus over those who had evil spirits, saying, &ldquo;I adjure you by Jesus whom Paul preaches!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="19:14">14</span></font></b> (Now seven sons of a certain Sceva, a Jewish chief priest, were doing this.) <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="19:15">15</span></font></b> But the evil spirit answered <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;answered&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said to them, &ldquo;Jesus I know, and Paul I am acquainted with, but who are you?&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="19:16">16</span></font></b> And the man <u>who had the evil spirit</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;in whom the evil spirit was.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> leaped on them, subdued all of them, <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;and&rdquo; is supplied because the two previous participles (&ldquo;leaped&rdquo; and &ldquo;subdued&rdquo;) have been translated as finite verbs."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> prevailed against them, so that they ran away from that house naked and wounded. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="19:17">17</span></font></b> And this became known to all who lived in Ephesus, both Jews and Greeks, and fear fell upon them all, and the name of the Lord Jesus was exalted. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="19:18">18</span></font></b> And many of those who had believed came, confessing and disclosing their practices, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="19:19">19</span></font></b> and many of those who practiced magic brought together <i>[their]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> books <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;brought together&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> burned <i>[them]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> up in the sight of everyone. And they counted up their value and found <i>[it was]</i> <u>fifty thousand silver coins</u>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;five ten thousands of silver coins.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="19:20">20</span></font></b> In this way the word of the Lord was growing in power and was prevailing. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="19:21">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="19:21">21</span></font></b> Now when these <i>[things]</i> were completed, Paul resolved in the Spirit to go to Jerusalem, passing through Macedonia and Achaia, saying, &ldquo;After I have been there, it is necessary <i>[for]</i> me to see Rome also.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="19:22">22</span></font></b> So <i>[after]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;sending&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> sending two of those who were assisting him, Timothy and Erastus, to Macedonia, he himself stayed <i>[some]</i> time in Asia.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A reference to the Roman province of Asia (modern Asia Minor)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="19:23">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="19:23">23</span></font></b> Now there happened at that time no little disturbance concerning the Way. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="19:24">24</span></font></b> For someone <u>named</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;by name.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Demetrius, a silversmith who made silver replicas of the temple of Artemis, was bringing no little business to the craftsmen. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="19:25">25</span></font></b> <u>These</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;whom.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> he gathered together, and the workers occupied with such things, <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;gathered together&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said, &ldquo;Men, you know that from this business <u>we get our prosperity</u>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;prosperity is to us.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="19:26">26</span></font></b> and you see and hear that not only in Ephesus but in almost all of Asia<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A reference to the Roman province of Asia (modern Asia Minor)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> this man Paul has persuaded <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;has persuaded&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> turned away a large crowd <i>[by]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[by]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;saying&rdquo;) which is understood as means."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> saying that the <i>[gods]</i> made by hands are not gods. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="19:27">27</span></font></b> So not only is there a danger this line of business of ours <i>[will]</i> come into disrepute, but also the temple of the great goddess Artemis <i>[will]</i> be regarded as nothing--and <i>[she]</i> is about to be brought down even from her grandeur, <i>[she]</i> whom the whole <i>[of]</i> Asia<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A reference to the Roman province of Asia (modern Asia Minor)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and the <i>[entire]</i> world worship!&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="19:28">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="19:28">28</span></font></b> And <i>[when they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;heard&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> heard <i>[this]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and became full of rage, they began to shout,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The imperfect tense has been translated as ingressive here (&ldquo;began to shout&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> saying, &ldquo;Great <i>[is]</i> Artemis of the Ephesians!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="19:29">29</span></font></b> And the city was filled with the tumult, and with one purpose they rushed into the theater, seizing Gaius and Aristarchus, Macedonians <i>[who were]</i> traveling companions of Paul. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="19:30">30</span></font></b> But <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;wanted&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Paul wanted to enter into the popular assembly, the disciples would not let him. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="19:31">31</span></font></b> And even some of the Asiarchs<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;provincial authorities.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> who were his friends sent <i>[word]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to him <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;sent&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> were urging <i>[him]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> not to risk himself <i>[by going]</i> into the theater. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="19:32">32</span></font></b> So some were shouting <i>[one thing]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> <i>[and]</i> some another, for the assembly was in confusion, and the majority did not know <u>why</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;on account of what.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> they had assembled. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="19:33">33</span></font></b> And <i>[some]</i> of the crowd advised<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;concluded <i>[it was about]</i>.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Alexander, <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;put ... forward&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the Jews put him forward. But Alexander, motioning <i>[with his]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> hand, was wanting to defend himself to the popular assembly. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="19:34">34</span></font></b> But <i>[when they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;recognized&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> recognized that he was a Jew, they were shouting with one voice from all <i>[of them]</i> for about two hours, &ldquo;Great <i>[is]</i> Artemis of the Ephesians!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="19:35">35</span></font></b> And <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;had quieted&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the city secretary had quieted the crowd, he said, &ldquo;Ephesian men, for who is there among men who does not know the Ephesian city is honorary temple keeper of the great Artemis and of <i>[her]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> image fallen from heaven? <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="19:36">36</span></font></b> Therefore <i>[because]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[because]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the causal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;are&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> these <i>[things]</i> are undeniable, it is necessary <i>[that]</i> you be quiet and do nothing rash! <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="19:37">37</span></font></b> For you have brought these men <i>[here]</i> <i>[who are]</i> neither temple robbers nor blasphemers of our goddess. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="19:38">38</span></font></b> If then Demetrius and the craftsmen <i>[who are]</i> with him have a complaint against anyone, the court days are observed and there are proconsuls--let them bring charges against one another! <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="19:39">39</span></font></b> But if you desire anything further, it will be settled in the lawful assembly. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="19:40">40</span></font></b> For indeed we are in danger of being accused of rioting concerning today, <i>[since there]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[since]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the causal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;is&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> is no cause in relation to which we will be able to give an account concerning this disorderly gathering!&rdquo; And <i>[when he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;had said&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> had said these <i>[things]</i>, he dismissed the assembly.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Verse 41 in the English Bible is included as part of v. 40 in the standard editions of the Greek text."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="20:1">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:1">20:1</span></font></b> Now after the turmoil had ceased, Paul summoned<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the participle (&ldquo;summoned&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb in keeping with English style."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the disciples, and <i>[after]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;encouraging&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> encouraging <i>[them]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> he said farewell <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;departed&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> departed to travel to Macedonia. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:2">2</span></font></b> And <i>[after he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;had gone through&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> had gone through those regions and encouraged them <u>at length</u>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;with many a word.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> he came to Greece <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:3">3</span></font></b> and stayed<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the participle (&ldquo;stayed&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb in keeping with English style."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> three months. <i>[Because]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[because]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the causal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;was made&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> a plot was made against him by the Jews <i>[as he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[as]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;was about to&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> was about to set sail for Syria, he came to a decision to return through Macedonia. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:4">4</span></font></b> And Sopater <i>[son]</i> of Pyrrhus from Berea, and Aristarchus and Secundus from Thessalonica, and Gaius from Derbe, and Timothy, and Tychicus and Trophimus from Asia, were accompanying him. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:5">5</span></font></b> And these had gone on ahead <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;had gone on ahead&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> were waiting for us in Troas. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:6">6</span></font></b> And we sailed away from Philippi after the days of Unleavened Bread and came to them at Troas within five days, where we stayed seven days. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="20:7">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:7">7</span></font></b> And on the first <i>[day]</i> of the week, <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;had assembled&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> we had assembled to break bread, Paul began conversing<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The imperfect tense has been translated as ingressive here (&ldquo;began conversing&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> with them, <i>[because he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[because]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;was going to&rdquo;) which is understood as causal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> was going to leave on the next day, and he extended <i>[his]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> message until midnight. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:8">8</span></font></b> Now there were quite a few lamps in the upstairs room where we were gathered. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:9">9</span></font></b> And a certain young man <u>named</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;by name.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Eutychus who was sitting in the window was sinking into a deep sleep <i>[while]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[while]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;was conversing&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Paul was conversing at length. Being overcome by sleep, he fell down from the third story and was picked up dead. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:10">10</span></font></b> But Paul went down <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;went down&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> threw himself on him, and putting his arms around <i>[him]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said, &ldquo;Do not be distressed, for his life is in him.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:11">11</span></font></b> So he went up and broke bread,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="This participle and the previous one (&ldquo;went up&rdquo;) have been translated as finite verbs in keeping with English style."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and <i>[when he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;had eaten&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> had eaten and talked for a long <i>[time]</i>, until dawn, then he departed. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:12">12</span></font></b> And they led the youth away alive, and <u>were greatly</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;were not moderately.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> comforted. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="20:13">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:13">13</span></font></b> But we went on ahead to the ship <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;went on ahead&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> put out to sea for Assos, intending to take Paul on board there. For having made arrangements in this way, he himself was intending to travel by land. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:14">14</span></font></b> And when he met us at Assos, we took him on board <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;took ... on board&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> went to Mitylene. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:15">15</span></font></b> And we sailed from there on the next <i>[day]</i>, <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;sailed&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> arrived opposite Chios. And on the next <i>[day]</i> we approached Samos, and on the following <i>[day]</i> we came to Miletus. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:16">16</span></font></b> For Paul had decided to sail past Ephesus so that he would not be <i>[having]</i> to spend time in Asia.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A reference to the Roman province of Asia (modern Asia Minor)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> For he was hurrying if it could be possible for him to be in Jerusalem on the day of Pentecost. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="20:17">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:17">17</span></font></b> And from Miletus he sent <i>[word]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to Ephesus <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;sent&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> summoned the elders of the church. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:18">18</span></font></b> And when they came to him, he said to them, &ldquo;You know from the first day on which I set foot in Asia<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A reference to the Roman province of Asia (modern Asia Minor)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> how I was the whole time with you-- <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:19">19</span></font></b> serving the Lord with all humility and with tears, and with the trials that happened to me through the plots of the Jews-- <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:20">20</span></font></b> how I did not shrink from proclaiming to you anything that would be profitable, and <i>[from]</i> teaching you in public and from house <i>[to house]</i>, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:21">21</span></font></b> testifying both to Jews and to Greeks with respect to repentance toward God and faith in our Lord Jesus. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="20:22">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:22">22</span></font></b> &ldquo;And now behold, bound by the Spirit I am traveling to Jerusalem, not knowing the things that will happen to me <u>there</u>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;in it.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:23">23</span></font></b> except that the Holy Spirit testifies to me in town <i>[after town]</i>, saying that bonds and persecutions await me. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:24">24</span></font></b> But I consider <i>[my]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> life <i>[as]</i> worth <u>nothing</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;not a single word&rdquo;; literally &ldquo;not any thing.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to myself, in order to finish my mission and the ministry that I received from the Lord Jesus, to testify <i>[to]</i> the gospel of the grace of God. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="20:25">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:25">25</span></font></b> &ldquo;And now behold, I know that all <i>[of]</i> you, among whom I went about proclaiming the kingdom, will see my face no more. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:26">26</span></font></b> Therefore I testify to you on this very day that I am guiltless of the blood of all <i>[of you]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The words &ldquo;<i>[of you]</i>&rdquo; are not in the Greek text but are implied."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:27">27</span></font></b> for I did not shrink from proclaiming to you the whole purpose of God. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:28">28</span></font></b> Be on guard for yourselves and for all the flock among which the Holy Spirit has appointed you <i>[as]</i> overseers, to shepherd the church of God which he obtained through the blood of his own <i>[Son]</i>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;through his own blood&rdquo;; the Greek construction can be taken either way, with &ldquo;Son&rdquo; implied if the meaning is &ldquo;through the blood of his own.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:29">29</span></font></b> I know that after my departure fierce wolves will come in among you, not sparing the flock. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:30">30</span></font></b> And from among you yourselves men will arise, speaking <u>perversions of the truth</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;crooked things.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> in order to draw away the disciples after them. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:31">31</span></font></b> Therefore be on the alert, remembering that night and day <i>[for]</i> three years I did not stop warning each one <i>[of you]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The words &ldquo;<i>[of you]</i>&rdquo; are not in the Greek text but are implied."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> with tears. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="20:32">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:32">32</span></font></b> &ldquo;And now I entrust you to God and to the message of his grace, which is able to build <i>[you]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> up and to give <i>[you]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the inheritance among all those who are sanctified. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:33">33</span></font></b> I have desired no one&apos;s silver or gold or clothing! <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:34">34</span></font></b> You yourselves know that these hands served <i>[to meet]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The words &ldquo;<i>[to meet]</i>&rdquo; are not in the Greek text but are supplied for clarity."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> my needs and <i>[the needs of]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The words &ldquo;<i>[the needs of]</i>&rdquo; are supplied in keeping with English style to maintain the parallelism with the earlier phrase &ldquo;my needs.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> those who were with me. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:35">35</span></font></b> I have shown you <i>[with respect to]</i> all <i>[things]</i> that <i>[by]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[by]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;working hard&rdquo;) which is understood as means."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> working hard in this way it is necessary to help those who are in need, and to remember the words of the Lord Jesus that he himself said, &ldquo;It is more blessed to give than to receive.&rdquo;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Perhaps an allusion to Matt 10:8; these exact words are not found in the NT gospels."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="20:36">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:36">36</span></font></b> And <i>[when he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;had said&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> had said these <i>[things]</i>, he fell to his knees <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;fell to&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> prayed with them all. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:37">37</span></font></b> And there was considerable weeping by all, and <u>hugging</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;falling on the neck of.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Paul, they kissed him, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:38">38</span></font></b> especially distressed at the statement that he had said, that they were going to see his face no more. And they accompanied him to the ship. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="21:1">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:1">21:1</span></font></b> And it happened that after we tore ourselves away<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the participle (&ldquo;tore ourselves away&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb in keeping with English style."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> from them, we put out to sea, <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous infinitive (&ldquo;put out to sea&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> running a straight course we came to Cos and on the next <i>[day]</i> to Rhodes, and from there to Patara. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:2">2</span></font></b> And finding a ship that was crossing over to Phoenicia, we went aboard <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;went aboard&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> put out to sea. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:3">3</span></font></b> And <i>[after we]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;sighted&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> sighted Cyprus and left it behind <u>on the port side</u>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;left.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> we sailed to Syria and arrived at Tyre, because the ship was to unload <i>[its]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> cargo there. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:4">4</span></font></b> And we stayed there seven days <i>[after we]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;found&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> found the disciples, who kept telling Paul through the Spirit not to set foot in Jerusalem. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:5">5</span></font></b> And it happened that when our days were over, we departed <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;departed&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> went on our way, <i>[while]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[while]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;accompanied&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> all <i>[of them]</i> accompanied us, together with <i>[their]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The word &ldquo;<i>[their]</i>&rdquo; is not in the Greek text but is implied."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> wives and children, as far as outside the city. And <i>[after]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;falling to&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> falling to our knees on the beach <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;and&rdquo; is supplied to join this and the previous participle (&ldquo;falling to&rdquo;) in keeping with English style."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> praying, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:6">6</span></font></b> we said farewell to one another and embarked in the ship, and they returned to their own <i>[homes]</i>. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="21:7">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:7">7</span></font></b> And <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;had completed&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> we had completed the voyage from Tyre, we arrived at Ptolemais. And <i>[after we]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;greeted&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> greeted the brothers, we stayed one day with them. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:8">8</span></font></b> And on the next day we departed <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;and&rdquo; is supplied to join this and the previous participle (&ldquo;departed&rdquo;) in keeping with English style."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> came to Caesarea, and entered into the house of Philip the evangelist, who was <i>[one]</i> of the seven, <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;and&rdquo; is supplied to join this and the previous participle (&ldquo;was&rdquo;) in keeping with English style."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> stayed with him. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:9">9</span></font></b> (<u>Now this man had</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;now to this man were.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> four virgin daughters who prophesied.) </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="21:10">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:10">10</span></font></b> And <i>[while we]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[while]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;were staying&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> were staying <i>[there]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> many days, a certain prophet <u>named</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;by name.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Agabus came down from Judea. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:11">11</span></font></b> And he came to us and took Paul&apos;s belt. Tying up his own feet and hands, he said, &ldquo;This is what the Holy Spirit says: &apos;In this way the Jews in Jerusalem will tie up the man whose belt this is, and will deliver <i>[him]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> into the hands of the Gentiles.&apos;&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:12">12</span></font></b> And when we heard these <i>[things]</i>, both we and the local residents urged him not to go up to Jerusalem. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:13">13</span></font></b> Then Paul replied, &ldquo;What are you doing weeping and breaking my heart? For I am ready not only to be tied up, but even to die in Jerusalem for the name of the Lord Jesus!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:14">14</span></font></b> And <i>[because]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[because]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the causal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;be persuaded&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> he would not be persuaded, we remained silent, saying, &ldquo;The will of the Lord be done.&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="21:15">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:15">15</span></font></b> So after these days we got ready <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;got ready&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> went up to Jerusalem. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:16">16</span></font></b> And <i>[some]</i> of the disciples from Caesarea also traveled together with us, bringing <i>[us]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to a certain Mnason of Cyprus, a disciple of long standing,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or perhaps &ldquo;one of the original disciples.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> with whom we were to be entertained as guests. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="21:17">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:17">17</span></font></b> And <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;came&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> we came to Jerusalem, the brothers welcomed us gladly. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:18">18</span></font></b> And on the next <i>[day]</i> Paul went in with us to James, and all the elders were present. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:19">19</span></font></b> And <i>[after]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;greeting&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> greeting them, he began to relate<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The imperfect tense has been translated as ingressive here (&ldquo;began to relate&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> <u>one after the other</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;with respect to each one.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> <i>[the things]</i> which God had done among the Gentiles through his ministry. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:20">20</span></font></b> And <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;heard&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> they heard <i>[this]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> they began to glorify<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The imperfect tense has been translated as ingressive here (&ldquo;began to glorify&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> God. And they said to him, &ldquo;You see, brother, how many ten thousands there are among the Jews who have believed, and they are all zealous adherents of the law. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:21">21</span></font></b> And they have been informed about you that you are teaching all the Jews <i>[who are]</i> among the Gentiles <i>[the]</i> abandonment of Moses, telling them not to circumcise <i>[their]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> children or to live according to <i>[our]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;according to the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> customs. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:22">22</span></font></b> What then <u>is to be done</u>?<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;is it.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Doubtless they will all hear that you have come! <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:23">23</span></font></b> Therefore do this that we tell you: <u>we have</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;there are to us.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> four men who have <i>[taken]</i> a vow upon themselves.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Some manuscripts have &ldquo;on themselves.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:24">24</span></font></b> Take these <i>[men]</i> <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;take&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> purify yourself along with them and <u>pay their expenses</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;spend on them.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> so that they can shave <i>[their]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> heads, and everyone will know that <i>[the things]</i> which they had been informed about you are nothing, but you yourself also agree with observing the law. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:25">25</span></font></b> But concerning the Gentiles who have believed, we have written a letter <i>[after]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;deciding&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> deciding they should avoid food sacrificed to idols and blood and <i>[what has been]</i> strangled and sexual immorality.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:26">26</span></font></b> Then Paul took along the men on the next day, <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; has been supplied in keeping with English style."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> <i>[after he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;had purified&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> had purified himself together with them, he entered into the temple <i>[courts]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[courts]</i>&rdquo; is supplied to distinguish this area from the interior of the temple building itself."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> announcing the completion of the days of purification until <u>the time</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;which <i>[time]</i>.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the offering would be presented on behalf of each one of them. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="21:27">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:27">27</span></font></b> But when the seven days were about to be completed, the Jews from Asia<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A reference to the Roman province of Asia (modern Asia Minor)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> who had seen him in the temple <i>[courts]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[courts]</i>&rdquo; is supplied to distinguish this area from the interior of the temple building itself."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> stirred up the whole crowd and laid hands on him, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:28">28</span></font></b> shouting, &ldquo;Israelite men, help! This is the man who is teaching everyone everywhere against the people and the law and this place! And furthermore he also brought Greeks into the temple, and has defiled this holy place!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:29">29</span></font></b> (For they had previously seen Trophimus the Ephesian in the city with him, whom they thought that Paul had brought into the temple.) <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:30">30</span></font></b> And the whole city was stirred up, and the people came running together, and they seized Paul <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;seized&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> dragged him outside of the temple <i>[courts]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[courts]</i>&rdquo; is supplied to distinguish this area from the interior of the temple building itself."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and immediately the doors were shut. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="21:31">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:31">31</span></font></b> And <i>[as they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[as]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;were seeking&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> were seeking to kill him, a report came up to the military tribune of the cohort that all Jerusalem was in confusion. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:32">32</span></font></b> <u>He</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;who.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> immediately took along soldiers and centurions <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;took along&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> ran down to them. And <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;saw&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> they saw the military tribune and the soldiers, they stopped beating Paul. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:33">33</span></font></b> Then the military tribune came up <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;came up&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> arrested him and ordered <i>[him]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to be bound with two chains, and inquired who he was and what it was that he had done. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:34">34</span></font></b> But some in the crowd were shouting one thing <i>[and]</i> others <i>[another]</i>, and <i>[because]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[because]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the causal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;able&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> he was not able to find out the truth on account of the commotion, he gave orders to bring him into the barracks.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;headquarters.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:35">35</span></font></b> And when he came to the steps, it happened that he had to be carried by the soldiers on account of the violence of the crowd, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:36">36</span></font></b> for the crowd of people was following <i>[them]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> shouting, &ldquo;Away with him!&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="21:37">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:37">37</span></font></b> And <i>[as he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[as]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;was about to&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> was about to be brought into the barracks,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;headquarters.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Paul said to the military tribune, &ldquo;Is it permitted for me to say something to you?&rdquo; And he said, &ldquo;Do you know Greek? <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:38">38</span></font></b> Then you are not the Egyptian who before these days raised a revolt and led out into the wilderness the four thousand men of the Assassins?&rdquo;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Also known as the &ldquo;Sicarii&rdquo; from the Latin word &ldquo;sicarius&rdquo; = dagger, after the short dagger used to assassinate political opponents."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:39">39</span></font></b> But Paul said, &ldquo;I am a Jewish man from Tarsus in Cilicia, a citizen of no unimportant city. Now I ask you, allow me to speak to the people.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:40">40</span></font></b> So <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;permitted&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> he permitted <i>[him]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Paul, standing there on the steps, motioned with <i>[his]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> hand to the people. And <i>[when there]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;was&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> was a great silence, he addressed <i>[them]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> in the Aramaic language, saying, </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="22:1">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:1">22:1</span></font></b> &ldquo;Men--brothers and fathers--listen to my defense to you now!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:2">2</span></font></b> And <i>[when they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;heard&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> heard that he was addressing them in the Aramaic language, <u>they became even more silent</u>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;they showed even more silence.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> And he said, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:3">3</span></font></b> &ldquo;I am a Jewish man born in Tarsus in Cilicia, but brought up in this city at the feet of Gamaliel, educated according to the exactness of the law received from our fathers, being zealous for God, just as all <i>[of]</i> you are today. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:4">4</span></font></b> <u>I</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;who.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> persecuted this Way to the death, tying up and delivering to prison both men and women, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:5">5</span></font></b> as indeed the high priest and the whole council of elders can testify about me, from whom also I received letters to the brothers in Damascus, <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;received&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> was traveling <i>[there]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to lead away those who were there also tied up to Jerusalem so that they could be punished. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="22:6">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:6">6</span></font></b> &ldquo;And it happened that <i>[as]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[as]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;was traveling&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> I was traveling and approaching Damascus around noon, suddenly a very bright light from heaven flashed around me, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:7">7</span></font></b> and I fell to the ground and heard a voice saying to me, &apos;Saul, Saul, why are you persecuting me?&apos; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:8">8</span></font></b> And I answered, &apos;Who are you, Lord?&apos; And he said to me, &apos;I am Jesus the Nazarene whom you are persecuting.&apos; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:9">9</span></font></b> (Now those who were with me saw the light but did not hear the voice of the one who was speaking to me.) <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:10">10</span></font></b> So I said, &apos;What should I do, Lord?&apos; And the Lord said to me, &apos;Get up <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;get up&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> proceed to Damascus, and there it will be told to you about all <i>[the things]</i> that have been appointed for you to do.&apos; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:11">11</span></font></b> And as I could not see as a result of the brightness of that light, I arrived in Damascus led by the hand of those who were with me. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:12">12</span></font></b> And a certain Ananias, a devout man according to the law, well spoken of by all the Jews who live <i>[there]</i>, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:13">13</span></font></b> came to me and stood by <i>[me]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;stood by&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said to me, &apos;Brother Saul, regain <i>[your]</i> sight!&apos; And <i>[at that]</i> same time I looked up at him <i>[and saw him]</i>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The words &ldquo;<i>[and saw him]</i>&rdquo; are not in the Greek text but are supplied in the translation for clarity."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:14">14</span></font></b> And he said, &apos;The God of our fathers has appointed you to know his will, and to see the Righteous One and to hear a voice from his mouth, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:15">15</span></font></b> because you will be a witness for him<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;to him.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to all people of what you have seen and heard. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:16">16</span></font></b> And now why are you delaying? Get up, be baptized, and wash away your sins, calling on his name!&apos; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="22:17">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:17">17</span></font></b> &ldquo;And it happened that <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;returned&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> I returned to Jerusalem and I was praying in the temple courts,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[courts]</i>&rdquo; is supplied to distinguish this area from the interior of the temple building itself."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> I was in a trance, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:18">18</span></font></b> and saw him saying to me, &apos;Hurry and depart <u>quickly</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;with quickness.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> from Jerusalem, because they will not accept your testimony about me.&apos; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:19">19</span></font></b> And I said, &apos;Lord, they themselves know that from synagogue <i>[to synagogue]</i> I was imprisoning and beating those who believed in you. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:20">20</span></font></b> And when the blood of your witness Stephen was being shed, I myself also was standing near and was approving, and was guarding the cloaks of those who were killing him.&apos; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:21">21</span></font></b> And he said to me, &apos;Go, because I will send you far away to the Gentiles!&apos;&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="22:22">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:22">22</span></font></b> Now they were listening to him until this word, and they raised their voices, saying, &ldquo;Away with such a man from the earth! For it is not fitting <i>[for]</i> him to live!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:23">23</span></font></b> And <i>[while]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[while]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;were screaming&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> they were screaming and throwing off <i>[their]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> cloaks and throwing dust into the air, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:24">24</span></font></b> the military tribune ordered him to be brought into the barracks,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;headquarters.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> saying he was to be examined with a lash so that he could find out for what reason they were crying out against him in this way. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:25">25</span></font></b> But when they had stretched him out for the lash,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;with straps&rdquo; (in order to lash him)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Paul said to the centurion standing there, &ldquo;Is it permitted for you to flog a man <i>[who is]</i> a Roman citizen and uncondemned?&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:26">26</span></font></b> And <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;heard&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the centurion heard <i>[this]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> he went to the military tribune <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;went to&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> reported <i>[it]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> saying, &ldquo;What are you about to do? For this man is a Roman citizen!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:27">27</span></font></b> So the military tribune came <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;came&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said to him, &ldquo;Tell me, are you a Roman citizen?&rdquo; And he said, &ldquo;Yes.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:28">28</span></font></b> And the military tribune replied, &ldquo;I acquired this citizenship for a large sum of money.&rdquo; And Paul said, &ldquo;But I indeed was born <i>[a citizen]</i>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The words &ldquo;<i>[a citizen]</i>&rdquo; are not in the Greek text but are implied."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:29">29</span></font></b> Then immediately those who were about to examine him kept away from him, and the military tribune also was afraid <i>[when he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;realized&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> realized that he was a Roman citizen and that <u>he had tied him up</u>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;he was having tied him up.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:30">30</span></font></b> But on the next day, <i>[because he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[because]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;wanted&rdquo;) which is understood as causal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> wanted to know the true <i>[reason]</i> why he was being accused by the Jews, he released him and ordered the chief priests and the whole Sanhedrin to assemble, and he brought down Paul <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;brought down&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> had <i>[him]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> stand before them. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="23:1">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:1">23:1</span></font></b> And looking intently at the Sanhedrin, Paul said, &ldquo;Men <i>[and]</i> brothers, I have lived my life in all good conscience before God to this day.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:2">2</span></font></b> So the high priest Ananias ordered those standing near him to strike his mouth. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:3">3</span></font></b> Then Paul said to him, &ldquo;God is going to strike you, <i>[you]</i> whitewashed wall! And are you sitting <i>[there]</i> judging me according to the law, and acting contrary to the law do you order me to be struck?&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:4">4</span></font></b> And those who stood nearby said, &ldquo;Are you reviling the high priest of God?&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:5">5</span></font></b> And Paul said, &ldquo;I did not know, brothers, that he was high priest. For it is written, &apos;You must not speak evil <i>[of]</i> a ruler of your people.&apos;&rdquo;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A quotation from Exod 22:28."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="23:6">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:6">6</span></font></b> Now <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;realized&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Paul realized that one part were Sadducees and the other Pharisees, he shouted out in the Sanhedrin, &ldquo;Men <i>[and]</i> brothers! I am a Pharisee, a son of Pharisees! I am being judged concerning the hope and the resurrection of the dead!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:7">7</span></font></b> And <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;said&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> he said this, a dispute developed between the Pharisees and Sadducees, and the assembly was divided. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:8">8</span></font></b> (For the Sadducees say there is no resurrection or angel or spirit, but the Pharisees acknowledge <i>[them]</i> all.) <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:9">9</span></font></b> And there was loud shouting, and some of the scribes from the party of the Pharisees stood up <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;stood up&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> contended sharply, saying, &ldquo;We find nothing wrong with this man! But <i>[what]</i> if a spirit or an angel has spoken to him?&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:10">10</span></font></b> And <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;became&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the dispute became severe, the military tribune, fearing lest Paul be torn apart by them, ordered the detachment to go down, take him away from their midst, and bring <i>[him]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> into the barracks.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;headquarters.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:11">11</span></font></b> And the next night the Lord stood by him <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;stood by&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said, &ldquo;Have courage, for as you have testified about me in Jerusalem, so you must also testify in Rome.&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="23:12">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:12">12</span></font></b> And <i>[when it]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;was&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> was day, the Jews made a conspiracy <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;made&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> bound themselves under a curse, saying <i>[they would]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;saying neither to eat nor to drink&rdquo;; the words &ldquo;they would&rdquo; are supplied for smoother English style."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> neither eat nor drink until they had killed Paul. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:13">13</span></font></b> Now there were more <i>[than]</i> forty who had made this conspiracy, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:14">14</span></font></b> who went to the chief priests and the elders <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;went to&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said, &ldquo;We have bound ourselves under a curse to partake of nothing until we have killed Paul. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:15">15</span></font></b> Therefore, now you along with the Sanhedrin explain to the military tribune that he should bring him down to you, as <i>[if you]</i> were going to determine more accurately the things concerning him. And we are ready to do away with him before he comes near.&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="23:16">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:16">16</span></font></b> But <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;heard about&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the son of Paul&apos;s sister heard about the ambush, he came and entered into the barracks<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;headquarters.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;and&rdquo; is supplied because the two previous participles (&ldquo;came&rdquo; and &ldquo;entered&rdquo;) have been translated as finite verbs."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> reported <i>[it]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to Paul. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:17">17</span></font></b> So Paul called one of the centurions <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;called&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said, &ldquo;Bring this young man to the military tribune, because he has something to report to him.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:18">18</span></font></b> So he took him <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;took&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> brought <i>[him]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to the military tribune and said, &ldquo;The prisoner Paul called me <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;called&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> asked <i>[me]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to bring this young man to you <i>[because he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[because]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;has&rdquo;) which is understood as causal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> has something to tell you.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:19">19</span></font></b> And the military tribune, taking hold of his hand and withdrawing privately, asked, &ldquo;What is it that you have to report to me?&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:20">20</span></font></b> And he said, &ldquo;The Jews have agreed to ask you that you bring Paul down to the Sanhedrin tomorrow, as <i>[if they]</i> were going to inquire somewhat more accurately concerning him. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:21">21</span></font></b> You therefore do not be persuaded by them, because more <i>[than]</i> forty men of <u>their number</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;them.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> are lying in wait <i>[for]</i> him, who have bound themselves under a curse neither to eat nor to drink until they have done away with him. And now they are ready, waiting for <u>you to agree</u>.&rdquo;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the assurance of agreement from you.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:22">22</span></font></b> So the military tribune sent the young man away, directing <i>[him]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> &ldquo;Tell no one that you have revealed these <i>[things]</i> to me.&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="23:23">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:23">23</span></font></b> And he summoned two of the centurions <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;summoned&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said, &ldquo;Make ready from the third hour of the night two hundred soldiers and seventy horsemen and two hundred spearmen,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A word of uncertain meaning, probably a military technical term."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> in order that they may proceed as far as Caesarea. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:24">24</span></font></b> And provide mounts so that they can put Paul on them <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;put ... on&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> bring <i>[him]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> safely to Felix the governor.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:25">25</span></font></b> <u>He wrote</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;writing.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> a letter that had this form:<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;content.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="23:26">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:26">26</span></font></b> Claudius Lysias. To his excellency Governor Felix.Greetings! <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:27">27</span></font></b> This man was seized by the Jews and was about to be killed by them <i>[when I]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;came upon&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> came upon <i>[them]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> with the detachment <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;came upon&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> rescued <i>[him]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> <i>[because I]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[because]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;learned&rdquo;) which is understood as causal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> learned that he was a Roman citizen. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:28">28</span></font></b> And <i>[because I]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[because]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;wanted&rdquo;) which is understood as causal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> wanted to know the charge for which they were accusing him, I brought <i>[him]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> down to their Sanhedrin.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;council.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:29">29</span></font></b> I found <u>he</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;whom.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> was accused concerning controversial questions of their law, but having no charge deserving death or imprisonment. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:30">30</span></font></b> And <i>[when it]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;was made known&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> was made known to me there would be a plot against the man, I sent <i>[him]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to you immediately, also ordering <i>[his]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> accusers to speak against him<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Some manuscripts have &ldquo;to state the charges against him&rdquo; (literally, &ldquo;to speak the <i>[things]</i> against him&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> before you. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="23:31">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:31">31</span></font></b> Therefore the soldiers, in accordance with <u>their orders</u>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;what was ordered to them.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> took Paul <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;took&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> brought <i>[him]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to Antipatris during the night. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:32">32</span></font></b> And on the next day they let the horsemen go on with him, <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;let&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> they returned to the barracks.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;headquarters.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:33">33</span></font></b> <u>The horsemen</u>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;who.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> <i>[when they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;came&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> came to Caesarea and delivered the letter to the governor, also presented Paul to him. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:34">34</span></font></b> So <i>[after]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;reading&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> reading <i>[the letter]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and asking what province he was from, and learning that <i>[he was]</i> from Cilicia, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:35">35</span></font></b> he said, &ldquo;I will give you a hearing whenever your accusers arrive also,&rdquo; giving orders <i>[for]</i> him to be guarded in the praetorium<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The &ldquo;praetorium&rdquo; of Herod refers to the palace of Herod the Great in Caesarea Maritima."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> of Herod. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="24:1">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:1">24:1</span></font></b> And after five days the high priest Ananias came down with some elders and an attorney, a certain Tertullus, all of whom brought charges against Paul to the governor. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:2">2</span></font></b> And <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;had been summoned&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> he had been summoned, Tertullus began to accuse <i>[him]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> saying, &ldquo;We have experienced<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here this participle (&ldquo;have experienced&rdquo;) and the following participle (&ldquo;are taking place&rdquo;) have been translated as finite verbs in keeping with English style."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> much<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;many <i>[years]</i>,&rdquo; with &ldquo;years&rdquo; understood."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> peace through you, and reforms are taking place in this nation through your foresight. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:3">3</span></font></b> Both in every <i>[way]</i> and everywhere we acknowledge <i>[this]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> most excellent Felix, with all gratitude. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:4">4</span></font></b> But so that I may not impose on you for longer, I implore you to hear us briefly with your <i>[customary]</i> graciousness. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:5">5</span></font></b> For we have found<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here this participle (&ldquo;found&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb in keeping with English style."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> this man <i>[to be]</i> a public menace and one who causes riots among all the Jews throughout the Roman Empire<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the inhabited earth,&rdquo; but here this is probably rhetorical hyperbole for the Roman Empire, especially since Felix, the Roman governor, is being addressed."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and a ringleader of the sect of the Nazarenes, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:6">6</span></font></b> who even attempted to desecrate the temple, and we arrested <u>him<font size=4>&nbsp;</u><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;whom.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </font>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Some later manuscripts include the following additional material between v. 6 and v. 8: &ldquo;and we wanted to judge him according to our law, (24:7) but Lysius the military tribune came and took him from our hands with much violence, (24:8) ordering his accusers to come before you.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:8">8</span></font></b> <i>[When]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;examine&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> you yourself examine <i>[him]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> you will be able to find out from <u>him</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;whom.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> about all these <i>[things]</i> of which we are accusing him.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:9">9</span></font></b> And the Jews also joined in the attack, asserting these <i>[things]</i> were so. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="24:10">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:10">10</span></font></b> And <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;gestured&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the governor gestured for him to speak, Paul replied, &ldquo;<i>[Because I]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[because]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;know&rdquo;) which is understood as causal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> know you have been a judge over this nation for many years, I defend myself cheerfully <i>[with respect to]</i> the things concerning myself. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:11">11</span></font></b> You can ascertain that <u>it has not been more than</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;there are not to me more than.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> twelve days <u>since</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;from which <i>[time]</i>.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> I went up to Jerusalem to worship. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:12">12</span></font></b> And neither did they find me arguing with anyone or making a crowd develop in the temple <i>[courts]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[courts]</i>&rdquo; is supplied to distinguish this area from the interior of the temple building itself."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> nor in the synagogues nor throughout the city. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:13">13</span></font></b> Nor can they prove <i>[the things]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to you concerning which they are now accusing me. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:14">14</span></font></b> But I do confess this to you, that according to the Way (which they call a sect), so I worship the God of our fathers, believing all things <i>[that are]</i> in accordance with the law and that are written in the prophets, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:15">15</span></font></b> having a hope in God which these <i>[men]</i> also themselves await: <i>[that]</i> there is going to be a resurrection of both the righteous and the unrighteous. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:16">16</span></font></b> <u>For this reason</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;by this.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> also <i>[I]</i> myself <u>always</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;through everything.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> do my best to have a clear conscience toward God and people. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:17">17</span></font></b> So after many years, I came to practice charitable giving and offerings to my people,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;nation.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:18">18</span></font></b> in which they found me purified in the temple <i>[courts]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[courts]</i>&rdquo; is supplied to distinguish this area from the interior of the temple building itself."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> not with a crowd or with a disturbance. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:19">19</span></font></b> But <i>[there are]</i> some Jews from Asia<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A reference to the Roman province of Asia (modern Asia Minor)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> who ought to be present before you and bring charges against <i>[me]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> if they have anything against me, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:20">20</span></font></b> or these <i>[men]</i> themselves should say what crime they found <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;stood&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> I stood before the Sanhedrin,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;council.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:21">21</span></font></b> other than concerning this one declaration that I shouted <i>[while]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[while]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;standing there&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> standing there before them: &apos;I am being judged before you today concerning the resurrection of the dead!&apos;&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="24:22">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:22">22</span></font></b> But Felix, <i>[because he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[because]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;understood&rdquo;) which is understood as causal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> understood the <i>[facts]</i> concerning the Way more accurately, put them off, saying, &ldquo;When Lysias the military tribune comes down, I will decide <u>your case</u>.&rdquo;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the <i>[case]</i> with respect to you.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:23">23</span></font></b> <i>[He]</i> ordered<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here this participle (&ldquo;ordered&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb in keeping with English style."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the centurion <i>[for]</i> him to be guarded and to have some freedom, and in no way to prevent any of his own <i>[people]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="This could refer to either friends or relatives."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> <i>[from]</i> serving him. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="24:24">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:24">24</span></font></b> And after some days, <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;arrived&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Felix arrived with his wife Drusilla, who was Jewish, he sent for Paul and listened to him concerning faith in Christ Jesus. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:25">25</span></font></b> And <i>[while]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[while]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;was discussing&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> he was discussing about righteousness and self control and the judgment that is to come, Felix became afraid <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;became&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> replied, &ldquo;Go away for the present, and <i>[when I]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;have&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> have an opportunity, I will summon you.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:26">26</span></font></b> At the same time he was also hoping that money would be given to him by Paul. For this reason also he sent for him as often as possible <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;sent for&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> talked with him. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:27">27</span></font></b> And <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;had passed&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> two years had passed, Felix received as successor Porcius Festus. And <i>[because he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[because]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;wanted&rdquo;) which is understood as causal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> wanted to do a favor for the Jews, Felix left Paul behind <u>as a prisoner</u>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;bound.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="25:1">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:1">25:1</span></font></b> Now <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;set foot in&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Festus set foot in the province, after three days he went up to Jerusalem from Caesarea. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:2">2</span></font></b> And the chief priests and the most prominent men of the Jews brought charges against Paul to him, and were urging him, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:3">3</span></font></b> asking for a favor against him, that he summon him to Jerusalem, <i>[because they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[because]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;were preparing &ldquo;) which is understood as causal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> were preparing an ambush to do away with him along the way. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:4">4</span></font></b> Then Festus replied <i>[that]</i> Paul was being kept at Caesarea, and <i>[he]</i> himself was about to go <i>[there]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> in a short time. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:5">5</span></font></b> So he said, &ldquo;Let those among you <i>[who are]</i> prominent go down with <i>[me]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;go down with&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> if there is any wrong in the man, let them bring charges against him.&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="25:6">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:6">6</span></font></b> And <i>[after he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;had stayed&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> had stayed among them not more than eight or ten days, he went down to Caesarea. On the next day he sat down on the judgment seat <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;sat down&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> gave orders <i>[for]</i> Paul to be brought. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:7">7</span></font></b> And <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;arrived&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> he arrived, the Jews who had come down from Jerusalem stood around him, bringing many and serious charges that they were not able to prove, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:8">8</span></font></b> <i>[while]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[while]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;said in his defense&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Paul said in his defense, &ldquo;Neither against the law of the Jews nor against the temple nor against Caesar have I sinned with reference to anything!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:9">9</span></font></b> But Festus, <i>[because he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[because]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;wanted&rdquo;) which is understood as causal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> wanted to do a favor for the Jews, answered <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;answered&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said to Paul, &ldquo;Are you willing to go up to Jerusalem to be tried before me there concerning these <i>[things]</i>?&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:10">10</span></font></b> But Paul said, &ldquo;I am standing before the judgment seat of Caesar, where it is necessary <i>[for]</i> me to be judged. I have done no wrong to the Jews, as you also know very well. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:11">11</span></font></b> If then I am doing wrong<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;I am in the wrong.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and have done anything deserving death, I am not trying to avoid<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the present tense has been translated as conative (&ldquo;trying to avoid&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> dying. But if there is nothing <i>[true]</i> of <i>[the things]</i> which these <i>[people]</i> are accusing me, no one can give me up to them. I appeal to Caesar!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:12">12</span></font></b> Then Festus, <i>[after]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;discussing&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> discussing <i>[this]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> with <i>[his]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> council, replied, &ldquo;You have appealed to Caesar--to Caesar you will go!&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="25:13">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:13">13</span></font></b> Now <i>[after]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;had passed&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> some days had passed, King Agrippa and Bernice arrived at Caesarea to welcome Festus. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:14">14</span></font></b> And while they were staying there many days, Festus laid out the <i>[case]</i> against Paul to the king, saying, &ldquo;There is a certain man left behind by Felix <i>[as]</i> a prisoner, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:15">15</span></font></b> concerning whom <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;was&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> I was in Jerusalem the chief priests and the elders of the Jews presented evidence, asking for a sentence of condemnation against him. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:16">16</span></font></b> To <u>them</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;whom.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> I replied that it was not the custom of the Romans to give up any man before the one who had been accused met <i>[his]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> accusers face to <i>[face]</i> and received an opportunity for a defense concerning the accusation. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:17">17</span></font></b> Therefore, <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;had assembled&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> they had assembled here, <i>[I]</i> made<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here this participle (&ldquo;made&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb in keeping with English style."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> no delay; on the next <i>[day]</i> I sat down on the judgment seat <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;and&rdquo; is supplied because the two previous participles (&ldquo;made&rdquo; and &ldquo;sat down&rdquo;) have been translated as finite verbs."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> gave orders <i>[for]</i> the man to be brought. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:18">18</span></font></b> <i>[When they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;stood up&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> stood up, <i>[his]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> accusers began bringing<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The imperfect tense has been translated as ingressive here (&ldquo;began bringing&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> no charge concerning <u>him</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;whom.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> of the evil deeds that I was suspecting, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:19">19</span></font></b> but they had some issues with him concerning their own religion, and concerning a certain Jesus, who was dead, whom Paul claimed to be alive. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:20">20</span></font></b> And <i>[because]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[because]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;was at a loss&rdquo;) which is understood as causal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> I was at a loss with regard to the investigation concerning these <i>[things]</i>, I asked if he was willing to go to Jerusalem and to be judged there concerning these <i>[things]</i>. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:21">21</span></font></b> But <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;appealed&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Paul appealed <i>[that]</i> he be kept under guard for the decision of His Majesty the Emperor, I gave orders <i>[for]</i> him to be kept under guard until I could send him to Caesar.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:22">22</span></font></b> So Agrippa <i>[said]</i> to Festus, &ldquo;I want to hear the man myself also.&rdquo; &ldquo;Tomorrow,&rdquo; he said, &ldquo;you will hear him.&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="25:23">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:23">23</span></font></b> So on the next day, Agrippa and Bernice came with great pageantry and entered into the audience hall, along with military tribunes and the most prominent men of the city. And <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;gave the order&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Festus gave the order, Paul was brought in. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:24">24</span></font></b> And Festus said, &ldquo;King Agrippa and all who are present with us, you see this man about whom the whole population of the Jews appealed to me, both in Jerusalem and here, shouting <i>[that]</i> he must not live any longer. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:25">25</span></font></b> But I understood <i>[that]</i> he had done nothing deserving death himself, and <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;appealed to&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> this man appealed to His Majesty the Emperor, I decided to send <i>[him]</i>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:26">26</span></font></b> I do not have anything definite to write to <i>[my]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> lord about <u>him</u>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;whom.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Therefore I have brought him before you <i>[all]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[all]</i>&rdquo; is supplied in the translation to indicate that the pronoun (&ldquo;you&rdquo;) is plural."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> --and especially before you, King Agrippa--so that <i>[after]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;has taken place&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> this preliminary hearing has taken place, I may have something to write. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:27">27</span></font></b> For it seems unreasonable to me to send a prisoner and not to indicate the charges against him.&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="26:1">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:1">26:1</span></font></b> So Agrippa said to Paul, &ldquo;It is permitted for you to speak for yourself.&rdquo; Then Paul extended <i>[his]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> hand <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;extended&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> began to defend himself:<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The imperfect tense has been translated as ingressive here (&ldquo;began to defend himself&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="26:2">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:2">2</span></font></b> &ldquo;Concerning all <i>[the things]</i> of which I am accused by the Jews, King Agrippa, I consider myself fortunate <i>[that]</i> before you I am about to defend myself today, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:3">3</span></font></b> <i>[because]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[because]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;are&rdquo;) which is understood as causal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> you are especially acquainted with both all the customs and controversial questions with respect to the Jews. Therefore I beg <i>[you]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to listen to me with patience. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="26:4">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:4">4</span></font></b> &ldquo;Now all the Jews know my manner of life from <i>[my]</i> youth, that had taken place from the beginning among my <i>[own]</i> people<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;nation.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and in Jerusalem, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:5">5</span></font></b> having known me for a long time, if they are willing to testify, that in accordance with the strictest party of our religion I lived <i>[as]</i> a Pharisee. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:6">6</span></font></b> And now I stand here on trial on the basis of hope in the promise made by God to our fathers, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:7">7</span></font></b> to which our twelve tribes hope to attain as <i>[they]</i> earnestly serve <i>[him]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> night and day. Concerning this hope I am being accused by the Jews, O king! <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:8">8</span></font></b> Why is it thought incredible by you <i>[people]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;people&rdquo; is supplied in the translation to indicate that the pronoun (&ldquo;you&rdquo;) is plural."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> that God raises the dead? <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:9">9</span></font></b> Indeed, I myself thought it was necessary to do many <i>[things]</i> opposed to the name of Jesus the Nazarene, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:10">10</span></font></b> which I also did in Jerusalem, and not only did I lock up many of the saints in prison, having received authority from the chief priests, but also <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;were being executed&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> they were being executed, I cast <i>[my]</i> vote<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;voting pebble,&rdquo; but here &ldquo;vote&rdquo; rather than &ldquo;voting pebble&rdquo; is used in the translation to avoid the idea that this small stone was actually thrown at the accused (it was used as a method of voting)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> against <i>[them]</i>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:11">11</span></font></b> And throughout all the synagogues I punished them often <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;punished&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> tried to force<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The imperfect tense has been translated as conative here (&ldquo;tried to force&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> <i>[them]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to blaspheme, and <i>[because I]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[because]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;was enraged&rdquo;) which is understood as causal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> was enraged at them beyond measure, I was pursuing <i>[them]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> even as far as to foreign cities. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:12">12</span></font></b> In <u>this activity</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;which.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> I was traveling to Damascus with the authority and full power of the chief priests. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:13">13</span></font></b> In the middle of the day along the road, O king, I saw a light from heaven, more than the brightness of the sun, shining around me and those who were traveling with me. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:14">14</span></font></b> And <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;had ... fallen&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> we had all fallen to the ground, I heard a voice saying to me in the Aramaic language, &apos;Saul, Saul, why are you persecuting me? <i>[It is]</i> hard for you to kick against the goads!&apos; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:15">15</span></font></b> So I said, &apos;Who are you, Lord?&apos; And the Lord said, &apos;I am Jesus whom you are persecuting. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:16">16</span></font></b> But get up and stand on your feet, because for this <i>[reason]</i> I have appeared to you, to appoint you a servant and witness both <i>[to the things]</i> in which you saw me and <i>[to the things]</i> in which I will appear to you, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:17">17</span></font></b> rescuing you from the people and from the Gentiles to whom I am sending you, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:18">18</span></font></b> to open their eyes <i>[so that they]</i> may turn from darkness to light and from the power of Satan to God, <i>[so that]</i> they may receive forgiveness of sins and a share among those who are sanctified by faith in me.&apos; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="26:19">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:19">19</span></font></b> &ldquo;Therefore, O King Agrippa, I was not disobedient to the heavenly vision, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:20">20</span></font></b> but to those in Damascus first, and in Jerusalem and all the region of Judea and to the Gentiles, I proclaimed <i>[that they should]</i> repent and turn to God, doing deeds worthy of repentance. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:21">21</span></font></b> On account of these <i>[things]</i> the Jews seized me in<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Some manuscripts have &ldquo;while I was in.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the temple <i>[courts]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[courts]</i>&rdquo; is supplied to distinguish this area from the interior of the temple building itself."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;seized&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> were attempting to kill <i>[me]</i>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:22">22</span></font></b> Therefore I have experienced help from God until this day, <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;have experienced&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> I stand here testifying to both small and great, saying nothing except what both the prophets and Moses have said were going to happen, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:23">23</span></font></b> that the Christ<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;Messiah.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> was to suffer <i>[and]</i> that <i>[as]</i> the first of the resurrection from the dead, he was going to proclaim light both to the people and to the Gentiles.&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="26:24">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:24">24</span></font></b> And <i>[as]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[as]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;was saying ... in his defense&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> he was saying these things in his defense, Festus said with a loud voice, &ldquo;You are out of your mind, Paul! <i>[Your]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> great learning <u>is driving</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;is turning.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> you <u>insane</u>!&rdquo;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;to madness.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:25">25</span></font></b> But Paul said, &ldquo;I am not out of my mind, most excellent Festus, but am speaking words of truth and rationality. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:26">26</span></font></b> For the king knows about these <i>[things]</i>, to whom also I am speaking freely, for I am not convinced <i>[that]</i> these <i>[things]</i> in any way have escaped<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Some manuscripts have &ldquo;that any of these <i>[things]</i> in any way has escaped.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> his notice, because this <u>was</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;is.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> not <u>done</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;having been done.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> in a corner. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:27">27</span></font></b> Do you believe the prophets, King Agrippa? I know that you believe.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:28">28</span></font></b> But Agrippa <i>[said]</i> to Paul, &ldquo;In a short time are you persuading me to become a Christian?&rdquo;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;In a short time you are persuading me to become a Christian.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:29">29</span></font></b> And Paul <i>[replied]</i>, &ldquo;I pray to God, whether in a short time or in a long time, not only you but also all those who are listening to me today may become such <i>[people]</i> as I also am, except for these bonds!&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="26:30">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:30">30</span></font></b> Both the king and the governor got up, and Bernice and those who were sitting with them. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:31">31</span></font></b> And <i>[as they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[as]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;were going out&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> were going out, they were talking to one another, saying, &ldquo;This man is not doing anything deserving death or imprisonment.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:32">32</span></font></b> And Agrippa said to Festus, &ldquo;This man could have been released if he had not appealed to Caesar.&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="27:1">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:1">27:1</span></font></b> And when it was decided <i>[that]</i> we would sail away to Italy, they handed over Paul and some other prisoners to a centurion <u>named</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;by name.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Julius of the Augustan<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The meaning and significance of the title &ldquo;Augustan&rdquo; is highly debated, as is the precise identification of this military unit; it may be an honorary unit designation given to auxiliary or provincial troops."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Cohort. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:2">2</span></font></b> And we went aboard a ship from Adramyttium that was about to sail to the places along the <i>[coast]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The word &ldquo;<i>[coast]</i>&rdquo; is not in the Greek text but is implied."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> of Asia<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A reference to the Roman province of Asia (modern Asia Minor)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;went aboard&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> put out to sea. Aristarchus, a Macedonian from Thessalonica, was with us. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:3">3</span></font></b> And on the next <i>[day]</i>, we put in at Sidon. And Julius, treating Paul kindly, allowed <i>[him]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to go to <i>[his]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> friends <u>to be cared for</u>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;to experience care.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:4">4</span></font></b> And from there we put out to sea <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;put out to sea&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> sailed under the lee of Cyprus, because the winds were against <i>[us]</i>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:5">5</span></font></b> And <i>[after we]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;had sailed across&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> had sailed across the open sea along Cilicia and Pamphylia, we put in at Myra in Lycia. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:6">6</span></font></b> And there the centurion found an Alexandrian ship sailing for Italy <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;found&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> put us <u>on board</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;into.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> it. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:7">7</span></font></b> And sailing slowly, in many days and with difficulty we came<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here this participle (&ldquo;came&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb in keeping with English style."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to Cnidus. <i>[Because]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[because]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the causal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;permit ... to go further&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the wind did not permit us to go further, we sailed under the lee of Crete off Salmone. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:8">8</span></font></b> And sailing along its coast with difficulty, we came to a certain place called Fair Havens, near which was the town <i>[of]</i> Lasea. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="27:9">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:9">9</span></font></b> And <i>[because]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[because]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the causal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;had passed&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> considerable time had passed and the voyage was now dangerous because even the Fast<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A reference to the Jewish Day of Atonement (Yom Kippur) which occurs in mid-autumn."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> was already over, Paul strongly recommended, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:10">10</span></font></b> saying to them, &ldquo;Men, I perceive that the voyage is going <u>to end</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;to be.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> with disaster and great loss, not only of the cargo and the ship, but also of our lives!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:11">11</span></font></b> But the centurion was convinced even more by the shipmaster and the shipowner than by what was said by Paul. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:12">12</span></font></b> And <i>[because]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[because]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the causal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;was&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the harbor was unsuitable for spending the winter in, the majority decided on a plan to put out to sea from there, if somehow they could arrive at Phoenix, a harbor of Crete facing toward the southwest and toward the northwest, to spend the winter <i>[there]</i>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="27:13">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:13">13</span></font></b> And <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;began to blow gently&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> a southwest wind began to blow gently, <i>[because they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[because]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;thought&rdquo;) which is understood as causal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> thought <i>[they]</i> could accomplish their purpose, they weighed anchor <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;weighed anchor&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> sailed close along Crete. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:14">14</span></font></b> But not long afterward a wind like a hurricane, called the northeaster,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;Euraquilo,&rdquo; a violent northern wind."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> rushed down from it.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="That is, from the island of Crete."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:15">15</span></font></b> And <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;was caught&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the ship was caught and <i>[was]</i> not able to head into the wind, we gave way <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;gave way&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> were driven <i>[along]</i>. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:16">16</span></font></b> And running under the lee of a certain small island called Cauda, we were able with difficulty to get the ship&apos;s boat under control. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:17">17</span></font></b> <i>[After]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;hoisting&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> hoisting <u>it up</u>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;which.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> they made use of supports to undergird the ship. And <i>[because they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[because]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;were afraid&rdquo;) which is understood as causal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> were afraid lest they run aground on the Syrtis, they lowered the sea anchor <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;lowered&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> thus were driven <i>[along]</i>. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:18">18</span></font></b> And <i>[because]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[because]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the causal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;battered by the storm&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> we were violently battered by the storm, on the next <i>[day]</i> <u>they began</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;they began to carry out.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> jettisoning <i>[the cargo]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:19">19</span></font></b> and on the third <i>[day]</i> they threw overboard the gear of the ship with their own hands. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:20">20</span></font></b> But <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;appeared&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> neither sun nor stars appeared for many days, and <i>[with]</i> not a little bad weather confronting <i>[us]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> finally all hope was abandoned <i>[that]</i> we would be saved. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="27:21">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:21">21</span></font></b> And <i>[because]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[because]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the causal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;were experiencing&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> many were experiencing lack of appetite, at that time Paul stood up in their midst <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;stood up&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said, &ldquo;Men, <i>[you]</i> ought to have followed my <i>[advice]</i> not to put out to sea from Crete, and <i>[thus]</i> avoided this damage and loss! <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:22">22</span></font></b> And now I urge you to cheer up, for there will be no loss of life from among you, but only of the ship. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:23">23</span></font></b> For this night an angel of the God whose I am and whom I serve came to me, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:24">24</span></font></b> saying, &apos;Do not be afraid, Paul! It is necessary <i>[for]</i> you to stand before Caesar, and behold, God has graciously granted you all who are sailing with you.&apos; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:25">25</span></font></b> Therefore keep up your courage, men, for I believe God that it will be like this--according to <u>the</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;which.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> way it was told to me. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:26">26</span></font></b> But it is necessary <i>[that]</i> we run aground on some island.&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="27:27">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:27">27</span></font></b> And when the fourteenth night had come, <i>[as]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[as]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;were being driven&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> we were being driven in the Adriatic Sea about the middle of the night, the sailors suspected <u>they were approaching some land</u>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;some land was approaching them.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:28">28</span></font></b> And taking soundings, they found twenty fathoms. So going on a little <i>[further]</i> and taking soundings again, they found fifteen fathoms. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:29">29</span></font></b> And <i>[because they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[because]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;were afraid&rdquo;) which is understood as causal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> were afraid lest somewhere we run aground against rough places, they threw down four anchors from the stern <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;threw down&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> prayed for day to come. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:30">30</span></font></b> And <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;were seeking&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the sailors were seeking to escape from the ship and were lowering the ship&apos;s boat into the sea, pretending as if they were going to lay out anchors from the bow, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:31">31</span></font></b> Paul said to the centurion and the soldiers, &ldquo;Unless these <i>[men]</i> remain with the ship, you cannot be saved!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:32">32</span></font></b> Then the soldiers cut away the ropes of the ship&apos;s boat and let it fall away.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;let it drift away.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="27:33">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:33">33</span></font></b> And until the day was about to come, Paul was urging <i>[them]</i> all to take <i>[some]</i> food, saying, &ldquo;Today <i>[is the]</i> fourteenth day you have waited <i>[anxiously]</i>, <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;have waited&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> you have continued without eating, having taken nothing. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:34">34</span></font></b> Therefore I urge you to take <i>[some]</i> food, for this is necessary for your preservation. For not a hair from your head will be lost.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:35">35</span></font></b> And <i>[after he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;said&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said these <i>[things]</i> and took bread, he gave thanks to God in front of <i>[them]</i> all, and <i>[after]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;breaking&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> breaking <i>[it]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> he began to eat. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:36">36</span></font></b> So they all were<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here this participle (&ldquo;were&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb in keeping with English style."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> encouraged and partook of food themselves. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:37">37</span></font></b> (Now we were <i>[in]</i> all two hundred seventy six persons on the ship.) <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:38">38</span></font></b> And <i>[when they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;had eaten their fill&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> had eaten their fill of food, they lightened the ship <i>[by]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[by]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;throwing&rdquo;) which is understood as means."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> throwing the wheat<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;grain.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> into the sea. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="27:39">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:39">39</span></font></b> Now when day came, they did not recognize the land, but they noticed a certain bay having a beach, onto which they decided to run the ship ashore if they could. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:40">40</span></font></b> And slipping the anchors, they left <i>[them]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> in the sea, at the same time loosening the ropes<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;bands&rdquo; (referring to the linkage that tied the steering oars together)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> of the steering oars. And hoisting the foresail to the <i>[wind]</i> that was blowing, they held course for the beach. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:41">41</span></font></b> But falling into a place of crosscurrents,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;a reef&rdquo;; literally &ldquo;a place of two seas,&rdquo; an expression of uncertain meaning but most likely a nautical technical term for some adverse sea condition."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> they ran the ship aground. And the bow stuck fast <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;stuck fast&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> stayed immovable, but the stern was being broken up by the violence.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Some manuscripts have &ldquo;the violence of the waves.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:42">42</span></font></b> Now the plan of the soldiers was that they would kill the prisoners lest any escape <i>[by]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[by]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;swimming away&rdquo;) which is understood as means."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> swimming away, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:43">43</span></font></b> but the centurion, <i>[because he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[because]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;wanted&rdquo;) which is understood as causal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> wanted to save Paul, prevented them <u>from doing what they intended</u>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;of the intention.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and gave orders <i>[that]</i> those who were able to swim should jump in first to get to the land, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:44">44</span></font></b> and <i>[then]</i> the rest, <i>[some]</i> of whom <i>[floated]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The word &ldquo;<i>[floated]</i>&rdquo; is not in the Greek text, but is supplied in the translation for clarity."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> on planks and <i>[some]</i> of whom on anything <i>[that was]</i> from the ship. And in this way all were brought safely to the land. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="28:1">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="28:1">28:1</span></font></b> And <i>[after we]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;were brought safely through&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> were brought safely through, then we found out that the island was called Malta. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="28:2">2</span></font></b> And the local inhabitants showed <u>extraordinary</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;not the ordinary.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> kindness to us, for they lit a fire <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;lit&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> welcomed us all, because of the rain that had begun and because of the cold. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="28:3">3</span></font></b> And <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;had gathered&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Paul had gathered a large number of sticks and was placing <i>[them]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> on the fire, a viper came out because of the heat <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;came out&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> fastened itself on his hand. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="28:4">4</span></font></b> And when the local people saw the creature hanging from his hand, they began saying<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The imperfect tense has been translated as ingressive here (&ldquo;began saying&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to one another, &ldquo;Doubtless this man is a murderer whom, <i>[although he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[although]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;was rescued&rdquo;) which is understood as concessive."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> was rescued from the sea, Justice<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here personified as a goddess."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> has not permitted to live!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="28:5">5</span></font></b> He, in turn, shook off the creature into the fire <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;shook off&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> suffered no harm. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="28:6">6</span></font></b> But they were expecting <i>[that]</i> he was going to swell up<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;to burn with fever&rdquo; (either meaning is possible here)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> or suddenly to fall down dead. So <i>[after]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;had waited&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> they had waited for a long <i>[time]</i> and saw nothing unusual happen to him, they changed their minds <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;changed their minds&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> began saying<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The imperfect tense has been translated as ingressive here (&ldquo;began saying&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> <i>[that]</i> he was a god. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="28:7">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="28:7">7</span></font></b> Now in the <i>[regions]</i> around that place were fields belonging to the chief official of the island, <u>named</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;by name.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Publius, who welcomed us <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;welcomed&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> entertained <i>[us]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> hospitably <i>[for]</i> three days. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="28:8">8</span></font></b> And it happened that the father of Publius was lying down, afflicted with fever and dysentery. Paul went<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here this participle (&ldquo;went&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb in keeping with English style."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to <u>him</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;whom.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and <i>[after]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;praying&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> praying, he placed <i>[his]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> hands on him <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;placed&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> healed him. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="28:9">9</span></font></b> And <i>[after]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;had taken place&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> this had taken place, the rest of those on the island who had diseases were coming and being healed also. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="28:10">10</span></font></b> They also honored us with many honors, and <i>[when we]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;putting out to sea&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> were putting out to sea, they gave <i>[us]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the <i>[things]</i> <u>we needed</u>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;for the needs.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="28:11">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="28:11">11</span></font></b> Now after three months we put out to sea in a ship that had wintered at the island, an Alexandrian <i>[one]</i> <u>with the twin gods Castor and Pollux as its insignia</u>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;marked with the Dioscuri&rdquo; (a joint name for the twin gods Castor and Pollux)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="28:12">12</span></font></b> And putting in at Syracuse, we stayed <i>[there]</i> three days. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="28:13">13</span></font></b> From there we got underway<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;we sailed along&rdquo; (with &ldquo;the coast&rdquo; understood); the exact meaning of the text as it stands is disputed and various additional terms have to be supplied in any case."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;got underway&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> arrived at Rhegium, and after one day a south wind came up <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;came up&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> on the second day we came to Puteoli, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="28:14">14</span></font></b> where we found brothers, <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;found&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> were implored to stay with them seven days. And in this way we came to Rome. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="28:15">15</span></font></b> And from there the brothers, <i>[when they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;heard&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> heard the <i>[news]</i> about us, came to meet us as far as the Forum of Appius and Three Taverns. <i>[When he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;saw&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> saw them, Paul gave thanks to God <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;gave thanks&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> took courage. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="28:16">16</span></font></b> And when we entered into Rome, Paul was allowed to stay by himself with the soldier who was guarding him. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="28:17">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="28:17">17</span></font></b> Now it happened that after three days, he called together those who were the most prominent of the Jews. And <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;had assembled&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> they had assembled, he said to them, &ldquo;Men <i>[and]</i> brothers, <i>[although]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[although]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;had done&rdquo;) which is understood as concessive."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> I had done nothing against <i>[our]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> people or the customs of our fathers, from Jerusalem I was delivered <i>[as]</i> a prisoner into the hands of the Romans, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="28:18">18</span></font></b> who, <i>[when they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;had examined&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> had examined me, were wanting to release <i>[me]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> because there was no basis for an accusation <i>[worthy]</i> of death with me. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="28:19">19</span></font></b> But <i>[because]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[because]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the causal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;objected&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the Jews objected, I was forced to appeal to Caesar (not as <i>[if I]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[if]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;had&rdquo;) which is understood as concessive."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> had any <i>[charge]</i> to bring against my <i>[own]</i> people).<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;nation.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="28:20">20</span></font></b> Therefore for this reason I have requested to see you and to speak with <i>[you]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> for because of the hope of Israel I am wearing this chain!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="28:21">21</span></font></b> And they said to him, &ldquo;We have received no letters about you from Judea, nor has any of the brothers come <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;come&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> reported or spoken anything evil about you. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="28:22">22</span></font></b> But we would like to hear from you what you think, for concerning this sect it is known to us that it is spoken against everywhere.&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="28:23">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="28:23">23</span></font></b> And <i>[when they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;had set&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> had set a day with him, many more came to him at his lodging place, to whom he was explaining from early in the morning until evening, testifying about the kingdom of God and attempting to convince<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the present tense has been translated as conative (&ldquo;attempting to convince&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> them about Jesus from both the law of Moses and the prophets. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="28:24">24</span></font></b> And <i>[some]</i> were convinced <i>[by]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[by]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;what was said&rdquo;) which is understood as means."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> what was said, but <i>[others]</i> refused to believe. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="28:25">25</span></font></b> So being in disagreement with one another, they began to leave <i>[after]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;made&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Paul made one statement: &ldquo;The Holy Spirit spoke rightly through the prophet Isaiah to your fathers, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="28:26">26</span></font></b> saying, &apos;Go to this people and say, &ldquo;<u>You will keep on hearing</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;hearing you will hear.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and will never understand, and <u>you will keep on seeing</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;seeing you will see.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and will never perceive. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="28:27">27</span></font></b> For the heart of this people has become dull, and with <i>[their]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> ears they hear with difficulty, and they have shut their eyes, lest they see with <i>[their]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> eyes, and hear with <i>[their]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> ears, and understand with <i>[their]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> heart, and turn, and I would heal them.&rdquo; &apos;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A quotation from Isa 6:9-10."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="28:28">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="28:28">28</span></font></b> Therefore let it be known to you that this salvation of God has been sent to the Gentiles. They also will listen!&rdquo;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Some later manuscripts include v. 29: &ldquo;And when he had said these things, the Jews departed, having a great dispute among themselves.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="28:30">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="28:30">30</span></font></b> So he stayed two whole years in his own rented house, and welcomed all who came to him, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="28:31">31</span></font></b> proclaiming the kingdom of God and teaching the <i>[things]</i> concerning the Lord Jesus Christ with all boldness, without hindrance. </p>
